"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731317","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-06-28","<p>Defra has been in regular contact, including in recent weeks, with officials from the Northern Ireland Executive on matters relating to the UK’s exit from the EU. I visited Northern Ireland in October 2016 to discuss issues including food labelling. The former Secretary of State visited in December to meet beef farmers, dairy processors and the Brexit Consultative Committee.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-06-28T15:56:21.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731317/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731317/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731317/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-06-21","Agriculture: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with officials of the Northern Ireland Executive and other key stakeholders in Northern Ireland on the implications of the UK leaving the EU for agri-food (a) producers and (b) labelling sectors.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731318","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-06-30","<p>Defra is working closely with the devolved administrations and stakeholders as we develop our approach to leaving the EU. I spoke at the Northern Ireland Food &amp; Drink Association Dinner on 18<sup>th</sup> October 2016 with a range of organisations in attendance, and met the Association again on 21<sup>st</sup> March 2017. The Secretary of State intends to visit Northern Ireland and meet stakeholders including the Ulster Farmers’ Unions in short order.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-06-30T16:09:51.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731318/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731318/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731318/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-06-21","Agriculture: Trade Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that the National and Ulster Farmers Unions and other key stakeholders are involved in discussions on negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731319","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-06-30","<p>We will provide stability to farmers as we leave the EU and we will continue to commit the same cash total in funds for farm support until the end of the parliament.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-06-30T14:49:15.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731319/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731319/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731319/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-06-21","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans he has to ensure that subsidy payments to farmers are maintained after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731320","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-06-28","<p>There is no agreed timetable for action by the EU.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-06-28T15:59:02.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731320/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731320/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731320/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-06-21","Microplastics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the timetable is for the EU to agree a ban on microbeads.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731321","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-06-28","<p>In England, we provide a range of payments to landowners, farmers and rural businesses through our Countryside Stewardship scheme and other rural grants and payments. Some of these are used to support land management for wildlife and other environment benefits and are open to a wide range of landowners or managers, including wildlife and conservation bodies. These payments cannot be used for land purchase.</p><p> </p><p>Defra and its non-departmental bodies have purchased land to provide compensation for habitat loss, working with wildlife and conservation bodies to ensure appropriate management: this does not involve provide funding for those bodies to acquire the land.</p><p> </p><p>We do provide grant-in-aid to the National Forest Company which is the charitable body established to lead on the development of the National Forest. Some of this funding can be used to acquire land for woodland planting and for promoting public enjoyment of woodland.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-06-28T16:03:29.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731321/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731321/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731321/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-06-21","Nature Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what support his Department gives to wildlife and conservation bodies to help purchase land for conservation and shooting purposes.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731322","Prime Minister","false","2017-06-30","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the press release issued on 11 June following my phone call with former Taoiseach Enda Kenny and which is available on the gov.uk website: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-call-with-taoiseach-enda-kenny-11-june-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/pm-call-with-taoiseach-enda-kenny-11-june-2017</a></p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-06-30T12:01:02.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731322/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731322/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731322/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-06-21","Borders: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what discussions she has had with the former Taoiseach Enda Kenny on the land border between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland as the UK exits the EU.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731323","Department for Transport","false","2017-06-28","<p>The Chris Gibb report was published by the Department for Transport on 22 June 2017. The report is now available on the GOV.UK website along with the Secretary of State’s response. Please see links provided: GOV.UK website link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/southern-rail-network-gibb-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/southern-rail-network-gibb-report</a></p><p> </p><p>SoS response link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/gibb-report-on-southern-rail-network-government-response" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/gibb-report-on-southern-rail-network-government-response</a></p><p> </p><p>As soon as we received the report, the Department assessed Chris Gibb’s technical recommendations against work or commitments that were already planned or underway. In early January we committed an extra £300m funding for Network Rail to boost the resilience of the infrastructure along the Brighton mainline and associated routes. The report could not be published during the pre-election period and we have published the report as soon as possible following the general election.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-06-28T14:17:11.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731323/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731323/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731323/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-21","Southern: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer of 24 April 2017 to Question 71377, on Southern: standards, on what date the Government plans to publish the report by Chris Gibb on performance of the Southern rail franchise; for what reasons the Government did not publish that report before the General Election; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731324","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>The independent exams regulator Ofqual, the awarding organisations and the Department for Education (DfE) have been providing, since 2014, a full range of information including guidance to teachers on the new 9 to 1 grading scale for reformed GCSEs in England. All awarding organisations must comply with Ofqual’s General Conditions of Recognition, which include rules related to the provision of effective guidance to schools and colleges (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/guidance-to-the-general-conditions-of-recognition" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/guidance-to-the-general-conditions-of-recognition</a>).</p><p> </p><p>Ofqual’s information campaign on the changes to GCSEs and the new grading scale has included speaking events, regular newsletters as well as blogs, postcards, webinars and advertising on social media and catch up television. Additionally, in July 2016 and March this year all schools and colleges were sent a joint DfE/Ofqual slide pack which provides teachers with a single source of information about the changes to GCSEs, and also to AS and A levels. This can be found at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/march-2017-ofqual-letter-to-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/march-2017-ofqual-letter-to-schools</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>More recently, on 20 and 21 June, we launched a new webpage (<a href="https://newgcses.campaign.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://newgcses.campaign.gov.uk/</a>) and fact sheets (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/gcse-new-grading-scale-factsheets" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/gcse-new-grading-scale-factsheets</a>) which provide information for teachers, and also for students, parents, employers, and others who work in education.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-06-29T16:06:27.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731324/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731324/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731324/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what training the Government is providing for teachers on the new GCSE grades system.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731325","Cabinet Office","false","2017-06-28","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-06-28T16:31:47.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731325/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731325/answer","PQ177 v.02.pdf","UKSA Response to PQ177","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731325/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-21","Capital Investment: Linlithgow and East Falkirk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much Government investment has been made in Linlithgow and East Falkirk constituency in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731326","Department for Transport","false","2017-06-26","<p>Network Rail are currently working with stakeholders on how best to provide an accessible route at Teddington. That process is due to finish shortly and they will then be able to estimate when the project will be complete, but this should be no later than March 2020.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-06-26T14:39:50.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731326/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731326/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731326/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-21","Teddington Station: Lifts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether work on the Access for All lift provision at Teddington Station will be completed by the end of 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731327","Department for Transport","false","2017-06-26","<p>As with all transport scheme proposals a thorough analysis is being carried out by my department to ensure it is a robust scheme. This includes examining whether the National Infrastructure Commission’s detailed recommendations on the scheme have been taken into account. The next steps and timescales will therefore be decided as part of this analysis.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-06-26T14:42:44.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731327/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731327/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731327/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-21","Crossrail 2 Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what timetable the Government has for completion of Crossrail 2.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731328","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-06-26","<p>An announcement will be made in due course.<em> <br></em></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-06-26T16:50:21.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731328/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731328/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731328/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-21","Planning: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when the planned 20 per cent increase in planning fees will be implemented.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731329","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-06-26","<p>Leaving the EU means we will want to take our own decisions about how to deliver the policy objectives previously targeted by EU funding. We are discussing closely with stakeholders all EU funding schemes, to ensure that any ongoing funding commitments best serve the UK‘s national interest.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-06-26T14:10:43.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731329/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731329/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731329/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-21","Culture: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether the Government plans to continue to participate in Creative Europe when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731330","Department for Education","false","2017-06-26","<p>The Education and Skills Funding Agency works constructively with local authorities and often uses sites secured from them to build free schools. This has proved increasingly effective since the inception of the programme.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-06-26T18:45:32.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731330/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731330/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731330/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Schools: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans to review the relationship between the Education and Skills Funding Agency and local education authorities regarding the provision of sites for new schools; and if she will make a statement on the effectiveness of current arrangements for such provision.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731331","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-06-26","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union, working with officials across Government, continues to undertake a wide range of analysis to support our negotiations. Our work covers the breadth of the UK economy, and we are looking in detail at more than 50 sectors as well as areas of cross-cutting regulation. Parliament has agreed that we will not publish anything that would undermine the Government’s ability to negotiate the best deal for Britain. Now, that the Prime Minister has initiated the Article 50 process and negotiations have begun in earnest, I can confirm that we will shortly be publishing the list of sectors we have been examining - though this of course does not mean that we have changed our position on revealing information which may harm our negotiating position.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-06-26T13:54:57.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731331/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731331/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731331/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-06-21","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to the Answer of 30 March 2017 to Question 69306, for what reason he believes the information requested would undermine the ability to negotiate the best possible deal for Britain.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731332","Department of Health","false","2017-06-27","<p>The burden of musculoskeletal (MSK) conditions is likely to rise significantly due to an ageing population and a combination of obesity and physical inactivity. Individual clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) and local authorities (LAs) are responsible for the delivery of services to treat and support the prevention of MSK disorders from their respective resources allocation. Where appropriate, some local services may be designed and delivered in partnership between CCGs and LAs.</p><p>Whilst not all MSK conditions are preventable, physical activity can play an important part in reducing risk of developing certain MSK disorders and managing MSK symptoms. Regular physical activity that meets national guidelines on frequency and intensity can reduce an individual’s risk of developing joint and back pain by 25% and can improve symptoms for people with MSK conditions.</p><p>The Department works with Public Health England (PHE), NHS England and local authorities to promote physical activity. The ‘Providing physical activity interventions for people with musculoskeletal conditions’ report, published in March 2017 is the result of collaboration between Arthritis Research UK, PHE, NHS England and the Department. The report reviews the benefits of physical activity both for people with MSK conditions and wider society and provides a framework that supports a tiered approach to intervention. More information can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.arthritisresearchuk.org/policy-and-public-affairs/reports-and-resources/reports/physical-activity-report.aspx" target="_blank">www.arthritisresearchuk.org/policy-and-public-affairs/reports-and-resources/reports/physical-activity-report.aspx</a></p><p>PHE is leading the discussions to engage all partners and stakeholders to prevent, detect and treat MSK conditions at an earlier stage through the use of evidence based interventions. For the whole population, the Government and PHE are also working to promote and support lifestyles that encourage people to make informed healthy choice in their approach to physical activity and eating a healthy diet, in order to promote overall wellbeing as well as reduce their risk of developing MSK conditions and to maintain and enhance bone health.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-06-27T10:30:34.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731332/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731332/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731332/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","Musculoskeletal Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to tackle the increase in the number of people diagnosed with arthritis and other musculoskeletal disorders in relation to (a) funding and (b) public health strategy.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731333","Cabinet Office","false","2017-06-28","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","7","2017-06-28T15:47:56.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731333/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731333/answer","PQs 7 and 255 v.02 (1) (1).pdf","UKSA Response to PQ7 and PQ255","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731333/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-21","Average Earnings: Linlithgow and East Falkirk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the average salary for (a) men, (b) women, (c) non-UK EU nationals in the Linlithgow and East Falkirk constituency was in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731334","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-06-29","<p>The protection of civilians in Syria is a priority for this Government. We will continue to support all efforts to reduce the level of violence in Syria, and use all diplomatic tools to work for a political solution which allows Syrians to decide their own future. The UK has played a leading role in the UN Security Council, supporting resolutions aimed at improving humanitarian access, civilian protection and investigating chemical weapons attacks.</p><p>We will continue to pursue accountability in Syria, including through support for robust EU sanctions against the Asad regime. With UK support, the EU now has sanctions in place against 240 persons and 67 entities linked to the violent repression of civilians in Syria. The UK will maintain support for the UN Commission of Inquiry which is reporting on human rights violations and abuses; and the International Impartial and Independent Mechanism (IIIM) whose role is to investigate and collect evidence of crimes committed in Syria. The UK is contributing to the start-up costs of the IIIM.</p><p>The UK continues to play a leading role in the fight against Daesh, which has been guilty of so many atrocities against civilians. We and the Coalition against Daesh take all allegations of civilian casualties seriously and ensure they are subsequently investigated. All possible precautions are taken to minimise the risk of civilian casualties when conducting any form of military operation. Through our rigorous targeting processes we will continue to seek to minimise the risk of civilian casualties.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-06-29T12:49:50.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731334/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731334/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731334/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-06-21","Syria: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to Together For Syria's Election 2017 manifesto, what steps he plans to take to work with the international community to protect civilians in Syria.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731335","Department of Health","false","2017-06-26","<p>As with other matters of conscience, abortion is an issue on which the Government adopts a neutral stance and allows Members to vote according to their moral, ethical or religious beliefs.</p><p> </p><p>The Abortion Act does not apply to Northern Ireland. Health, and by extension abortion law in Northern Ireland, is a transferred matter and is the responsibility of Northern Ireland Executive Ministers.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-06-26T13:21:54.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731335/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731335/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731335/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","Abortion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the Government's policy is on changing the law on abortion in (a) England and Wales and (b) Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731336","Department for Education","false","2017-06-30","<p>I am sorry, but data on these matters are not collected centrally by the Department for Education. Each local authority maintains its own records of such interventions.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","213","2017-06-30T08:11:32.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731336/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731336/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731336/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Home Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many interventions have been made by social services relating to home schooling in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731337","Department of Health","false","2017-06-27","<p>NHS England and Public Health England announced in December 2016 that up to £10 million is to be made available to run a three year trial for pre-exposure prophylaxis to answer outstanding questions about future access and implementation. Work continues to ensure a robust trial starting as quickly as possible. Following the drug procurement, NHS England expects to be able to confirm the award of the final contract no later than the first week of August, meaning trial drugs could be available from early August, in readiness for the trial to begin once ethics approval is received and trial sites are prepared.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-06-27T10:35:58.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731337/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731337/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731337/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","HIV Infection: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when the Pre-Exposure Prophylaxis impact trial will begin; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731338","Department of Health","false","2017-06-27","<p>The Government is committed to reducing smoking prevalence in pregnant women and will be publishing its new Tobacco Control Plan for England shortly. This will aim to reduce smoking prevalence generally and includes actions to reduce smoking during pregnancy.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England continues to work closely with NHS England to increase the number of women having a smoke-free pregnancy through a variety of initiatives. This is a key priority within NHS England’s Maternity Transformation Programme and a key action to reduce stillbirths and meet the Secretary of State’s ambition to halve the number of stillbirths by 2030, and to reduce stillbirths by 20% by 2020.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-06-27T10:33:23.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731338/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731338/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731338/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","Pregnancy: Smoking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to reduce smoking amongst pregnant women.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731339","Department of Health","false","2017-06-27","<p>The revised timeline for the review of the nutrient profiling model was published on gov.uk on 30 March 2017 and is available to view here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/review-of-the-nutrient-profiling-model" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/review-of-the-nutrient-profiling-model</a></p><p> </p><p>The revised timescales are set to ensure that the options for the review of the nutrient profiling model are fully considered through a transparent process and will uphold the latest government recommendations for sugar and fibre.</p><p> </p><p>The review of the nutrient profiling model is due to be completed by June 2018.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-06-27T10:23:24.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731339/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731339/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731339/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","Nutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when the timescales on the new nutrient profile model will be published; and for what reasons the publications of those timescales has been delayed.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731340","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-06-30","<p>We will listen to the views of everyone who has an interest in the future of the farming industry as we prepare new approaches to supporting food production and stewardship of the countryside.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-06-30T14:40:28.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731340/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731340/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731340/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-06-21","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if his Department will take steps to ensure agricultural subsidies for farmers and landowners are used to enhance access to places the public can walk in.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731341","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-06-28","<p>I refer the right hon. Member to the Scottish Partnerships (Register of People with Significant Control) Regulations 2017. S.I. 2017 No. 694.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-06-28T12:57:50.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731341/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731341/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731341/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-21","Limited Liability: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he plans to bring Scottish Limited Partnerships within the scope of the register of persons of significant control.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731342","Department for Education","false","2017-07-04","<p>Alongside the rest of Government, we will take forward any findings from the public inquiry and ensure any recommendations for schools are implemented.</p><p> </p><p>All schools must comply with strict building and fire safety regulations. It has always been the case that sprinklers are installed in new school buildings if a risk assessment identifies them as necessary or if they are required under a local planning policy. There are no plans whatsoever to introduce any changes that would make fire safety laws for schools less strict.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-04T15:25:56.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731342/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731342/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731342/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Schools: Fire Extinguishers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if her Department will make it a requirement that all schools are fitted with sprinkler systems for fire safety; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","258"
