"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731346","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-06-27","<p>We are committed to ensuring our welfare system is a strong safety net for those with disabilities and long-term health conditions. We will ensure that support is both sustainable and targeted to those who need it most, and will continually look at ways of improving the delivery of disability benefits. The Government received around 6000 responses to the Improving Lives Green Paper on work, health and disability. We are carefully considering the Consultation responses and next steps will be outlined in due course.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-06-27T14:39:36.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731346/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731346/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731346/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-06-21","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his policy is on benefits for disabled people over the course of this Parliament.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731347","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-06-28","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The existing surplus-sharing arrangements have worked well to date for the Scheme’s members. The presence of the Government guarantee has enabled the Scheme Trustees to invest so as to target surpluses, which has resulted in a 30% increase in payments to members. The Department cannot unilaterally amend the terms of the scheme, though we would be willing to consider any proposals put forward by the Scheme Trustees.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-06-28T14:16:08.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731347/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731347/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731347/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-21","Mineworkers' Pension Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will enter into negotiations with the Mineworkers Pension Scheme Trustees to discuss the current surplus sharing arrangements.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731348","Department of Health","true","2017-06-29","<p>We are making £1.4 billion available by 2020 to improve the provision of children and young people’s mental health services (CYP MH), including £<ins class="ministerial">150</ins><del class="ministerial">250</del> million specifically to tackle eating disorders.</p><p> </p><p>This funding is delivering a major system-wide transformation programme to improve access and make services more widely available across the country, and implementing the vision set out in Future in Mind. To this end all clinical commissioning groups working with their partners, developed CYP MH Transformation Plans in 2015/16, incorporating them last year into their wider National Health Service Sustainability and Transformation Plans. These set out how local agencies are working together to improve children and young people’s mental health across the full spectrum of need.</p><p> </p><p>Later this year, the Government will publish a Green Paper on Children and Young People’s Mental Health focused on helping our youngest and most vulnerable members of society receive the best start in life. This will make sure best practice is being used consistently and will help to accelerate improvements across all services so that children and young people get the right mix of prevention and specialist support.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-06-29T14:46:46.147Z","2017-07-04T15:00:32.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731348/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731348/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731348/answer","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731348/answer/previousversion/791","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to (a) improve mental health provision and (b) support the needs of children and young people.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731349","Cabinet Office","false","2017-06-28","<p>The Government stated in its manifesto a commitment to maintain the voting age at 18. The Government therefore has no plans to lower the voting age in elections.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-06-28T16:25:49.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731349/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731349/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731349/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-21","Voting Rights: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to lower the voting age to 16.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731350","Department of Health","false","2017-06-26","<p>The National Health Service is required to meet its operational standards as set out in the mandate and ensure access to appropriate care for all, in line with the NHS constitution. It is right that the NHS should consider efficiency savings such as reducing delayed transfers of care, reducing running costs, or reviewing treatments that are of low clinical effectiveness – because this improves patient care overall.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","386","2017-06-26T16:51:38.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731350/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731350/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731350/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of potential changes to NHS expenditure resulting from the new capped expenditure process arising from (a) limiting the number of operations carried out by non-NHS providers, (b) drawing out waiting times for planned care, (c) stopping NHS funding for some treatments, (d) closing wards and theatres and reducing staffing, (e) closing or downgrading services, including emergency or maternity units, (f) selling estate and other property-related transactions and (g) stopping prescriptions for some items.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731351","Home Office","false","2017-06-27","<p>The information you have requested is not included in statistics published by the Home Office.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-06-27T10:54:57.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731351/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731351/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731351/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-21","Nurses: Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many visas to work in the UK have been issued for people taking up nursing positions in the NHS in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731352","Department of Health","false","2017-06-27","<p>NHS Digital publishes data on the nationality of staff working in the National Health Service in England. Nationality is self-reported within the NHS human resources and payroll system, the electronic staff record.</p><p> </p><p>As of 31 March 2017, latest data available, there are now 137,384 (headcount) foreign nationals, or 11.6% employed in the National Health Service trusts and clinical commissioning groups. 80,822 of NHS staff records do not contain useful data with people choosing not to specify their nationality or not asked to.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-06-27T15:33:37.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731352/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731352/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731352/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","NHS: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many foreign nationals are working in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731353","Department of Health","false","2017-06-27","<p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State has not received any representations from Cabinet colleagues about reintroducing the National Health Service bursary for new pre-registration nursing, midwifery and allied health students from 1 August 2017.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-06-27T15:25:11.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731353/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731353/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731353/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations he has received from Cabinet colleagues about reintroducing the student nursing bursary.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731354","Cabinet Office","false","2017-06-29","<p>Discussions between the Conservative and Democratic Unionist Parties were on a political basis. Minutes were not taken.</p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-06-29T15:15:09.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731354/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731354/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731354/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-21","Queen's Speech","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will publish minutes of the meetings between Ministers and the Democratic Unionist Party on supporting the Queen's Speech 2017.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731355","Cabinet Office","false","2017-06-27","<p>The Government has no plans to establish an independent body to set rules for and formalise general election leaders debates.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-06-27T14:55:00.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731355/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731355/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731355/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-21","General Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will establish an independent body to set rules for and formalise general election leaders debates.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731356","Department of Health","false","2017-06-26","<p>The National Health Service and wider health system has examined how to sustain and improve care – which produced the NHS Five Year Forward View. The Government committed to providing an additional £10 billion in real terms by 2020-21 to back the NHS’ plan, enabling it to deliver key priorities like seven day care, improved access to cancer treatments and better mental health services.</p><p> </p><p>Since then, this Government has committed to increase NHS spending by a minimum of £8 billion in real terms over the next five years, and for the first time to deliver an increase in real funding per head of the population for every year of the parliament. As with all public services, the NHS needs to live within the budget agreed.</p><p> </p><p>As the NHS itself has said, it is unfair if a small number of areas in effect take more than their fair share of that budget at the expense of other people’s hospital services, general practitioner care and mental health clinics elsewhere in the country. Although financial performance across the NHS has significantly improved over the past year, a few areas have not yet finalised their plans to keep within their budget, as the NHS is required to by the 2017/18 Government Mandate.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","385 ; 446 ; 447 ; 448","2017-06-26T16:21:23.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731356/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731356/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731356/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when final plans for savings in each local area affected by the new capped expenditure process in the NHS will be agreed; who has final responsibility for agreeing those plans; and when and by whom those final plans will be made public.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731357","Department of Health","false","2017-06-27","<p>Health Education England (HEE) provide estimates of staff shortages as part of their Workforce Plan for England publication. The latest figures are available at the following link.</p><p><a href="https://hee.nhs.uk/sites/default/files/documents/Workforce%20Plan%20for%20England%202016-17.pdf" target="_blank">https://hee.nhs.uk/sites/default/files/documents/Workforce%20Plan%20for%20England%202016-17.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>HEE plan to publish the Workforce Plan for England 2017/18 in due course.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-06-27T15:31:48.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731357/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731357/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731357/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","NHS: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of staff shortages in the NHS by number and position.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731358","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-04","<p>The Government stated in its manifesto its intention to repeal the Fixed-term Parliaments Act.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-07-04T15:19:23.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731358/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731358/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731358/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-21","Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will repeal the Fixed-terms Parliaments Act 2011.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731359","Department of Health","false","2017-06-29","<p>Spending on mental health is not reported per head. NHS England will be incorporating a spend per head metric into their Mental Health published information from 2017/18.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-06-29T14:46:48.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731359/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731359/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731359/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","Mental Health Services: Per Capita Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much per person the NHS has spent on treating people with mental health conditions in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731360","Cabinet Office","false","2017-06-27","<p>The Conservative Party manifesto included a commitment to ensure that the House of Lords continues to fulfil its constitutional role as revising and scrutinising chamber which respects the primacy of the House of Commons and to ensure the work of the House of Lords remains relevant and effective by addressing issues such as its size.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-06-27T14:57:22.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731360/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731360/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731360/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-21","House of Lords: Reform","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will bring forward legislative proposals on the reform of the House of Lords to make that House accountable to the electorate.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731361","Cabinet Office","false","2017-06-27","<p>The Government’s view is that the First Past the Post system is well-established here. In each constituency, candidates are elected to represent the views of their constituents and in each case a candidate for whom more people voted than for any of the alternatives is elected. The current system also provides a clear and well-understood link between constituents and their representative in Parliament and is well-understood by the electorate. The Government does not have plans to change the voting system for General Elections.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-06-27T14:43:56.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731361/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731361/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731361/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-21","Electoral Systems","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will consider alternative voting systems for general elections and introduce a proportional system.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731362","Department of Health","false","2017-06-29","<p>Average waiting times from referral date to first treatment appointment date are available in the monthly Improving Access to Psychological Therapies publications. These are based on referrals entering treatment in the month, rather than patients, since it is possible for a single person to have more than one referral at any particular time.</p><p> </p><p>The latest monthly publication of February 2017 data is available from:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.content.digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB24016" target="_blank">http://www.content.digital.nhs.uk/catalogue/PUB24016</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-06-29T14:49:17.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731362/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731362/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731362/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","Mental Health Services: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average waiting time is between a patient being diagnosed with a mental health issue and receiving access to counselling and talking therapies.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731363","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-30","<p>I refer the honourable member to the comments made by the Chancellor regarding the public sector pay cap during the debate on the Queen’s speech on 29 June. Link to those exchanges is available at <a href="http://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2017-06-29/debates/D199DEF4-2B92-4D43-BF7D-01F7D98591A3/EconomyAndJobs" target="_blank">http://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2017-06-29/debates/D199DEF4-2B92-4D43-BF7D-01F7D98591A3/EconomyAndJobs</a></p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-06-30T12:53:19.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731363/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731363/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731363/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-21","Public Sector: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will lift the one per cent pay cap.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731364","Department of Health","false","2017-06-27","<p>The number of days lost in the National Health Service due to staff absence other than sickness is not collected centrally. The number of days lost to the NHS as a result of sickness absence over the last five years is in the table below <sup>1</sup> .</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Sum of Full Time Equivalent sick days taken</p></td><td><p>Sum of Full Time Equivalent working days available</p></td><td><p>Sickness absence rate (%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>15,970,492</p></td><td><p>376,888,359</p></td><td><p>4.24 %</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>15,424,804</p></td><td><p>377,092,245</p></td><td><p>4.09 %</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>16,178,672</p></td><td><p>384,714,386</p></td><td><p>4.21 %</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>16,346,443</p></td><td><p>392,433,945</p></td><td><p>4.17 %</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>16,866,471</p></td><td><p>403,377,016</p></td><td><p>4.18 %</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Note:</p><p><sup>1</sup> Source: NHS Digital - NHS Staff Sickness Absence Statistics. The data includes the number of days between the start and end dates of each sickness absence episode, even those days on which the employee would not have normally worked. This has an effect of overestimating the total sick days.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-06-27T15:20:17.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731364/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731364/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731364/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","NHS: Lost Working Days","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many days have been lost in the NHS due to staff absence and sickness in  each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731365","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-06-29","<p>This Government is committed to supporting our high streets. We have confirmed the permanent doubling of Small Business Rate Relief, meaning that 600,000 small businesses now pay no business rates at all; we launched the High Street pledge and a digital high street pilot scheme; and we are celebrating our high streets through the hugely successful Great British High Street Awards.</p><p>High streets can benefit from funding that we have made available for local economic development, including the Coastal Communities Fund, which has invested over £132 million in 131 coastal projects across England since 2012. The Government has also awarded £9.1 billion to Local Enterprise Partnerships in Growth Deals since 2014.</p><p>We are working with Local Enterprise Partnerships to strengthen their role in town centres and coastal communities, and collaborating with the Local Government Association to assist local authorities in supporting their high streets.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2017-06-29T17:34:37.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731365/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731365/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731365/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-21","Retail Trade: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make available funding for the renewal and redevelopment of high streets.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731366","Home Office","false","2017-06-26","<p>This is an operational matter for the police. How they enforce the law, including road traffic law and how available resources are deployed, are the responsibility of individual Chief Constables, taking into account the specific local problems and demands with which they are faced.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-06-26T16:11:23.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731366/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731366/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731366/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-21","A19: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to increase patrols and speeding enforcement at accident blackspots on the A19.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731367","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-03","<p>Local authorities already have a range of compulsory purchase powers to acquire and develop land that is derelict, neglected or unsightly provided there is a compelling case in the public interest for the authority's redevelopment scheme.</p><p>In addition other powers available to a local authority to act include section 215 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990, to serve a notice requiring owners to clean up land and buildings where their condition adversely affects the amenity of the area; Section 79 – 81 of the Environmental Protection Act 1990 to serve an abatement notice to carry out works on any premises where its condition is such as to be prejudicial to health, or, amounts to a nuisance; Section 29 of the Local Government (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1982 to secure any unoccupied building against unauthorised entry and undertake works to prevent it becoming a danger to public health; and Section 76 of the Building Act 1984 to require property owners to remedy defective buildings that are in such a condition as to be prejudicial to health or amount to a nuisance.</p><p>There are no other powers to require owners to sell or develop their land.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-03T16:05:12.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731367/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731367/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731367/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-21","Derelict Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to give local authorities the power to (a) take over or (b) mandate owners to develop, sell or clear blight and derelict sites suitable for commercial or residential development.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731368","Home Office","false","2017-06-26","<p>The Home Office does not hold the specific information requested.</p><p>The Home Office collects data annually on the primary function of police officers. Under the functions framework there is no dedicated function for fraud. However, there is a dedicated function for officers working primarily on ‘Economic crime’, which includes officers working in financial investigation units, cheque and credit card fraud units, regional asset recovery teams, and other financial investigations.</p><p>Officers with multiple responsibilities or designations are recorded under their primary function. The data do not therefore provide a complete picture of all officers who work on economic crime.</p><p>Data on the number of officers working primarily on economic crime can be found in Table F4, under function 7c, of the ‘Police workforce’ statistics published in July 2016: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/544954/police-workforce-tabs-jul16.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/544954/police-workforce-tabs-jul16.ods</a></p><p>Any comparisons at force level should be made with care due to collaboration arrangements between forces for particular functions. Additionally, police functions data are often affected by re-structuring within police forces. Therefore comparisons over time may not be meaningful.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-06-26T16:16:44.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731368/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731368/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731368/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-21","Police: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many dedicated officers there are in each police force that specialise in fraud.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731369","Home Office","false","2017-06-26","<p>Allocation of resources to specific areas of operational policing is a local matter for Police and Crime Commissioners (PCCs) and Chief Officers. While police forces should include within their policing and budget plans reasonable contingencies for unexpected events within their areas, if they face unexpected or exceptional events there is an established process by which PCCs can apply for Special Grant funding to help with these costs.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-06-26T16:14:04.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731369/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731369/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731369/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-21","Police: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will bring forward legislative proposals to provide police forces with additional resources when handling complex fraud cases.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731370","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-28","<p>Local authorities already have strong powers to tackle poor property conditions.</p><p>We encourage local authorities to take action where properties are neglected and their condition adversely affects the amenity of an area. There are already extensive powers available to authorities which range from notices under section 215 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 which can deal with derelict land and buildings to section 29 of the Local Government (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1982 for works on unoccupied buildings.</p><p>Council and housing association landlords are responsible for most repairs to their housing stock. Social landlords are obliged, by law, to maintain the structure and exterior of their properties.</p><p>All properties in the social and private sectors must comply with the Housing Health and Safety Rating System. Where a property has serious hazards that present a risk to health and safety, local authorities can carry out an assessment under the Housing Health and Safety Rating System. If they are aware of a serious hazard, they are under a duty to take appropriate action to address it.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-28T11:01:36.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731370/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731370/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731370/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-21","Private Property: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will grant local authorities the power to insist that landlords or home owners maintain their properties to an acceptable standard where that condition is having a negative impact upon the local community.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731371","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-06-30","<p>Local authorities have discretion over whether to set fees for dealing with high hedges complaints and to set their level. Part 8 of the Anti-social Behaviour Act 2003, the high hedges legislation, enables local authorities in England to charge fees for intervening in unresolved neighbour disputes about tall evergreen hedges. Decisions on setting such fees are a matter for each local authority and has been since the legislation was implemented.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-06-30T10:22:03.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731371/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731371/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731371/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-21","Hedges and Ditches: Mediation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will introduce legislative proposals to abolish or reduce the fees local authorities charge to mediate high-hedge disputes under the Anti-social Behaviour Act 2003 and the High Hedges Regulations 2005.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731372","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-28","<p>The locations of the letting agent fee ban workshops were chosen to make the exercise as inclusive as possible to those interested in attending. Venues were selected based on availability, size and ease of access.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-28T10:38:47.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731372/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731372/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731372/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-21","Letting Agents: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what criteria were used to select the location of letting agents' fees ban workshops.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731373","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-10","<p>Under the Housing Health and Safety Rating System, older polystyrene ceiling tiles that are identified in rented accommodation inspections as being a fire risk, can be subject to an Improvement Notice served by the Local Authority, requiring their removal. Failure to comply with an improvement Notice is a criminal offence, for which local authorities can impose a financial penalty of up to £30,000 or prosecute in the courts which have the power to impose an unlimited fine.</p><p>Unmodified polystyrene ceiling tiles do not comply with Building Regulations guidance , and so any new build home or other building should not be using them.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-10T14:49:45.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731373/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731373/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731373/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-21","Rented Housing: Fire Hazards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to prohibit the use of polystyrene ceiling tiles in rented accommodation.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731374","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-06-29","<p>Unmodified polystyrene ceiling tiles do not comply with Part B of the Building Regulations (fire) and should not be used in new buildings.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-06-29T17:27:40.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731374/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731374/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731374/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-21","Buildings: Fire Hazards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what fire risk assessments have been carried out on the use of polystyrene ceiling tiles; and whether this product should be removed from the market.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731375","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-06-30","<p>DCMS has worked with a number of local communities to progress community broadband schemes and, as a result, information and guidance for communities has been developed and published on the Department’s website: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/community-led-broadband-schemes. This also includes case studies such as Broadband for the Rural North (B4RN) (https://b4rn.org.uk/) and other examples.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-06-30T11:49:59.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731375/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731375/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731375/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-21","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions her Department has had with representatives of community broadband schemes in England about the roll-out of superfast broadband services.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731376","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-06-28","<p>The consultation on driving offences and penalties issued by the previous government closed on 1 February. The government is now considering the consultation responses. Any announcement will be made in due course.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-06-28T15:27:26.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731376/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731376/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731376/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-21","Road Traffic Offences: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when his Department plans to publish its response to the consultation that closed on 1 February 2017 on driving offences and penalties relating to causing death or serious injury.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731377","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-06-28","<p>The UK remains firmly opposed to the death penalty in all circumstances. We have repeatedly called upon the Government of Pakistan to end capital punishment and, at a minimum, commit publicly to renewing the previously imposed moratorium on the death penalty. We regularly raise our concerns about freedom of expression and the misuse of the blasphemy laws with the Government of Pakistan at a senior level. Our concerns are reflected in the latest update to the Foreign and Commonwealth Office annual human rights report.</p><p>The Foreign Secretary raised religious tolerance and misuse of the blasphemy laws during his visit to Pakistan in November 2016. My predecessor, my Hon. Friend the Member for Reading West (Mr Sharma), discussed the death penalty and the importance we attach to freedom of expression with Kamran Michael, Pakistani Minister for Human Rights, and Barrister Zafarullah Khan, the Prime Minister's Special Assistant for Human Rights, during his visit to Pakistan in January 2017.</p><p>The Government will continue to urge Pakistan to honour in practice its human rights obligations, including those related to the death penalty and freedom of expression and religion.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-06-28T14:44:21.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731377/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731377/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731377/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-06-21","Taimoor Raza","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has had discussions with the Government of Pakistan on the death sentence for blasphemy placed on Taimoor Raza.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731378","Home Office","false","2017-06-28","<p>Partners from across Government, the police and the security services are considering what more can be done to prevent terrorist attacks using vehicles, including the use of hire vehicles. This is wide ranging work and includes consideration as to whether and where increased sharing of data and more effective use of intelligence systems and processes may assist these efforts.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-06-28T13:00:47.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731378/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731378/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731378/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-21","Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will allocate resources to ensure that van hire firms and the police are able to share intelligence and information in order to prevent terrorist attacks using hired vans as weapons.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731379","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-06-30","<p>In January, I wrote to the Northern Ireland political parties to seek their views on moving to full transparency for Northern Ireland political donations and loans. I received a positive response from the parties. The introduction of increased transparency of donations to Northern Ireland parties was also a Conservative Manifesto commitment at the recent Parliamentary election. I will make a statement shortly on the steps needed to ensure that information relating to Northern Ireland political donations and loans can be published.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-06-30T13:32:28.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731379/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731379/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731379/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-06-21","Political Parties: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, if he will set out a timetable to introduce legislation ending the practice allowing anonymity for donations to political parties operating in Northern Ireland; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","1"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731380","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-06-29","<p>The UK Government is resolute in defending the country from terrorism and other threats. I commend An Garda Síochána on their success in seizing a large quantity of plastic explosives which, had it been used, could have caused death or serious injury. I intend to discuss how we can build upon positive work with An Garda Síochána when I next meet the Irish Justice Minister. There is a need for continued vigilance as dissident republican terrorists maintain their lethal intent.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-06-29T12:20:05.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731380/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731380/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731380/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-06-21","Explosives: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions the Government has had with the Government of the Republic of Ireland on the (a) seizure of substantial amounts of Semtex in Dublin on 3 June 2017, (b) capacity of dissident republican groups to obtaining Semtex and (c) response of An Garda Síochiná to those incidents.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","2"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731381","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-06-30","<p>The regulation of activities in Lough Foyle and Carlingford Lough is the responsibility of the Loughs Agency, a cross-border body established under the Belfast Agreement of 1998. We remain fully committed to these arrangements and continue to work closely with the Irish Government over improvements to the management of the Loughs.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-06-30T13:34:16.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731381/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731381/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731381/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-06-21","Carlingford Lough and Lough Foyle","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what the Government's policy is on the jurisdictional status of (a) Lough Foyle and (b) Carlingford Lough; and what recent discussions have been held with the Government of the Republic of Ireland on those disputed jurisdictions.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","3"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731382","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-07-04","<p>Cases of suspected electoral fraud are an operational matter for the Chief Electoral Officer who has referred a small number of cases relating to the Parliamentary general election to the PSNI for investigation. Any allegations of suspected malpractice should be reported to the PSNI and the Electoral Office for Northern Ireland.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-07-04T11:54:16.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731382/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731382/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731382/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-06-21","Election Offences: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what information he has received on instances of voter fraud in the 2017 General Election; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","4"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731383","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-06-29","<p><em></em>As responsibility for libel law in Northern Ireland is devolved, it would be for the Northern Ireland Executive to determine whether there should be any changes to Northern Ireland libel law.</p><p><em><br> <br> <br> </em></p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-06-29T14:15:20.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731383/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731383/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731383/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-06-21","Defamation: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, if he will initiate consultation on aligning libel law in Northern Ireland with that in England and Wales; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","5"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731384","Leader of the House","false","2017-06-29","<p>The Government undertook a technical review of the Standing Orders relating to English Votes for English Laws in October 2016. A report was subsequently published on 30 March 2017 in which the Government concluded that the procedures introduced by English Votes have shown to be working well and do not require substantive change at this time. However, Parliament and the Government will continue to work together in monitoring the operation of the procedures.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>A copy of the report can be found at the below address:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/english-votes-for-english-laws-review" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/english-votes-for-english-laws-review</a></p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2017-06-29T16:16:57.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731384/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731384/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731384/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2017-06-21","English Votes for English Laws","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, if she will introduce proposals to rescind standing orders relating to English votes for English laws; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","6"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731385","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-06-29","<p>We recognise that this is a difficult and sensitive issue, and have set up procedures that are mindful of the sensitivities involved. To claim the exception the claimant will need to provide a completed pro-forma from an approved third party or evidence relating to either a relevant criminal conviction or relevant award of criminal injuries compensation. DWP staff will not question the claimant about the incident, they will only take the claim and receive the supporting documents. Claimants will be asked to confirm that they are not living with the other biological parent of the child during the process of providing evidence. They will not be asked to identify the alleged perpetrator.</p><p>Where a pro-forma is provided from a third party, DWP staff will check that the form is complete and verified by an approved third party. Where other evidence is provided this will be checked and returned to the claimant.</p><p>The decision regarding entitlement to the exception will be subject to the normal mandatory reconsideration and appeal process.</p><p>DWP will hold exception information for the duration of an open claim and then for 14 months after a claim is closed. This is in accordance with standard procedures and to ensure that the 14 month maximum appeal period for decisions is observed.</p><p>Where a claimant moves between Child Tax Credit and Universal Credit, the information with regard to the exception will be shared between DWP and HMRC to prevent the claimant from having to provide evidence for the exception a second time. A secure data transfer method has been set up to manage this process. In the case of an appeal, information will be shared with HMCTS to facilitate the appeal. This will be managed in line with data protection requirements.</p><p>Any disclosure request for information in relation to the exception would be considered in liaison with the prosecuting authority as appropriate, in accordance with procedures and practice applicable in the jurisdiction concerned and taking account of particular circumstances, including the relevance of the documents requested to the case and all applicable legal considerations including those relating to data protection.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","11 ; 12 ; 15 ; 17 ; 22","2017-06-29T11:06:20.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731385/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731385/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731385/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-06-21","Social Security Benefits: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what evidence a claimant will have to provide to secure an exemption in relation to support for a child conceived without your consent.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","10"
