than Ashworth","448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731472","Department of Health","false","2017-06-26","<p>The National Health Service and wider health system has examined how to sustain and improve care – which produced the NHS Five Year Forward View. The Government committed to providing an additional £10 billion in real terms by 2020-21 to back the NHS’ plan, enabling it to deliver key priorities like seven day care, improved access to cancer treatments and better mental health services.</p><p> </p><p>Since then, this Government has committed to increase NHS spending by a minimum of £8 billion in real terms over the next five years, and for the first time to deliver an increase in real funding per head of the population for every year of the parliament. As with all public services, the NHS needs to live within the budget agreed.</p><p> </p><p>As the NHS itself has said, it is unfair if a small number of areas in effect take more than their fair share of that budget at the expense of other people’s hospital services, general practitioner care and mental health clinics elsewhere in the country. Although financial performance across the NHS has significantly improved over the past year, a few areas have not yet finalised their plans to keep within their budget, as the NHS is required to by the 2017/18 Government Mandate.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","446 ; 447 ; 448 ; 450","2017-06-26T16:21:23.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731472/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731472/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731472/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, who in his Department has lead responsibility for the new capped expenditure process in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731473","Department of Health","false","2017-06-26","<p>The National Health Service is required to meet its operational standards as set out in the mandate and ensure access to appropriate care for all, in line with the NHS constitution. It is right that the NHS should consider efficiency savings such as reducing delayed transfers of care, reducing running costs, or reviewing treatments that are of low clinical effectiveness – because this improves patient care overall.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","449","2017-06-26T16:51:38.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731473/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731473/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731473/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","Patients' Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to protect and promote patient's rights under the NHS constitution in those areas affected by the new NHS capped expenditure process.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731474","Home Office","false","2017-06-26","<p>The Government keeps the legislation relating to air weapons in England and Wales under review. High-powered air weapons require a firearms licence and low-powered air weapons are already subject to a range of controls, such as the requirement that owners take reasonable precautions to prevent young people from gaining unauthorised access to air weapons. Guidance is published on the safe use and storage of air weapons and this can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/117804/air-weapons-safety-leaflet.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/117804/air-weapons-safety-leaflet.pdf</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-06-26T16:19:06.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731474/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731474/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731474/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-21","Airguns","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of introducing a requirement that air rifles should be kept in a locked cabinet; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","74"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731475","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-06-26","<p>No central assessment has been carried out. The costs will vary widely based on the size and age of buildings. Local authorities may have commissioned separate assessments into the costs involved following the Government’s request in 2013 to social housing providers that they consider installing sprinklers into older residential tower blocks.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-06-26T16:49:04.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731475/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731475/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731475/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-21","High Rise Flats: Fire Extinguishers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will publish all assessments carried out into the costs of retrofitting sprinklers in high-rise, multi-occupied residential buildings since 2013.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","78"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731476","Home Office","false","2017-08-04","<p>The Home Office does not hold information on how many inspection and enforcement staff have been employed to audit premises.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-08-04T14:37:39.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731476/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731476/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731476/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-21","Fire Prevention: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many inspection and enforcement staff have been employed to audit premises under the Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 in each Fire Safety Authority in England in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","79"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731477","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-06-26","<p>Cladding using a composite aluminium panel with a polyethylene core would be non-compliant with current Building Regulations guidance, if used as cladding on buildings over 18 metres in height.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-06-26T16:28:13.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731477/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731477/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731477/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-21","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether Reynobond PE aluminium panels are banned for use as cladding on high-rise residential tower blocks in the UK.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","80"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731478","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-30","<p>The Government is strongly supportive of both the co-operative and social enterprise sectors. The Government supports social enterprises in various ways, including championing procurement for social value. At Spring Budget 2017, the Government also announced that the thresholds at which co-operatives will have to conduct a full audit will increase in line with those for companies. This will allow co-operatives to use more of their resources to benefit their members. The Government will continue to explore further ways to support the sector.</p><p> </p><p>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery. Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</a>.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","117 ; 1202","2017-06-30T11:24:32.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731478/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731478/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731478/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-21","Cooperatives and Social Enterprises","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans his Department has to support the growth of the co-operative and social enterprise sector.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731479","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-30","<p>The Government is strongly supportive of both the co-operative and social enterprise sectors. The Government supports social enterprises in various ways, including championing procurement for social value. At Spring Budget 2017, the Government also announced that the thresholds at which co-operatives will have to conduct a full audit will increase in line with those for companies. This will allow co-operatives to use more of their resources to benefit their members. The Government will continue to explore further ways to support the sector.</p><p> </p><p>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery. Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</a>.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","116 ; 1202","2017-06-30T11:24:32.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731479/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731479/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731479/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-21","Cooperatives","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with his European counterparts on measures aimed at supporting the growth of the co-operative sector.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731480","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-06-28","<p>This Government is committed to empowering communities and these projects, which put local people in the driving seat, are an important part of a clean, secure and affordable energy system. We applaud the work done by the local council in the hon. Member’s own constituency with the Plymouth Energy Community.</p><p>Since 2013, the UK Government has committed over £16m to support community energy. This includes the Rural Community Energy Fund which continues to offer feasibility and development finance for renewable energy projects. Community renewable energy projects also remain eligible to apply for the Renewable Heat Incentive (RHI) and Feed-in Tariff (FIT) scheme.</p><p>We are pleased to support events of the current Community Energy Fortnight (24<sup>th</sup> June – 7<sup>th</sup> July) and are reviewing the latest State of the Sector report by Community Energy England.</p><p>This Government sees community energy as an important part of a wider local energy ecosystem; with cities, municipalities and local partners driving this agenda. As such we have already committed funding to identify and overcome local barriers to delivery in the short term while we understand the contribution and importance of this sector to the delivery of both the Industrial Strategy and the Clean Growth Plan.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-06-28T12:49:48.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731480/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731480/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731480/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-21","Renewable Energy: Community Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans his Department has to support community-owned renewable energy.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731481","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-06-28","<p>Under current planning assumptions HMS Swiftsure, as the demonstrator submarine, will allow the Submarine Dismantling Project to define and refine initial dismantling and recycling processes by Quarter one of 2022 and inform future contractual arrangements. The Ministry of Defence's Disposal Services Authority will agree with the successful contractor the optimum arrangement for removal of the submarine for conventional recycling, including time-scales.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-06-28T15:28:32.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731481/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731481/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731481/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-06-21","Submarines: Decommissioning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he expects the first Royal Navy submarine to have been fully recycled under the Submarine Dismantling Project.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731482","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-06-28","<p>As we move towards the Type 26 Global Combat Ships entering service with the Royal Navy in the 2020s, preparations will include consideration of their future base porting.</p><p>The Type 31e programme is in its pre-concept phase, therefore, no decisions have yet been taken on base porting arrangements.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-06-28T15:25:44.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731482/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731482/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731482/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-06-21","Frigates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he expects to decide on base porting arrangements between Devonport and Portsmouth for the new (a) Type 26 and (b) Type 31 frigates.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731483","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-26","<p>As a rule, insurers use their claims experience and other industry-wide statistics to assess the risks posed by an individual and set the terms and price at which they will offer insurance cover. Insurers make an assessment of risk based on the likelihood of the individual making a claim and the potential cost of that claim.</p><p> </p><p>However, the Government remains concerned about the impact on motor insurance premiums from the continuing high number and cost of whiplash claims. This is why we committed in the Queen’s Speech to take firm action to reform the whiplash claims process and reduce the financial burden on consumers.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-06-26T14:51:53.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731483/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731483/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731483/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-21","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 27 April 2017 to Question 71682, what plans the Government has to review its policy on insurance premiums.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731484","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-06-28","<p>We will set out our plans to fulfil our manifesto commitment in due course.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-06-28T15:51:02.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731484/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731484/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-06-21","Fisheries: Treaties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when the Government plans to trigger the UK's exit from the London Convention.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731485","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-06","<p>All those whose homes were destroyed in the fire, who have approached services for assistance have been provided with emergency hotel accommodation. Housing Needs Assessments have been conducted with 138 households and suitable temporary accommodation is currently being identified for them until such time as permanent social housing can be offered<strong>.</strong></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","66","2017-07-06T15:04:10.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731485/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731485/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-21","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many survivors of the Grenfell Tower fire who have been recorded as made statutory homeless have been re-housed by the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea Council (a) in London boroughs neighbouring Kensington and Chelsea, (b) in London boroughs not neighbouring Kensington and Chelsea and (c) outside London.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731486","Prime Minister","false","2017-06-30","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the Statement made by the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, my right hon. Friend the Member for Bromsgrove (Mr Javid) on 26 June 2017, Official Report, column 347</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May","139","2017-06-30T12:02:08.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731486/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731486/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-06-21","High Rise Flats: Fire Regulations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, with reference to her statement of 17 June 2017 on the Grenfell Tower disaster, how many local authorities have been approached about enforcement of fire orders in high-rise buildings; how many such buildings have been found to be non-compliant with orders; and on what date she expects to have completed checks with all local authorities.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731487","Prime Minister","false","2017-06-30","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the Statement made by the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, my right hon. Friend the Member for Bromsgrove (Mr Javid) on 26 June 2017, Official Report, column 347</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May","138","2017-06-30T12:02:08.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731487/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731487/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-06-21","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, with reference to her statement of 17 June 2017 on the Grenfell Tower disaster, how many fire safety reviews are to be conducted into housing association and local authority high-rise buildings similar to Grenfell Tower; and on what date all such reviews are expected to conclude.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731488","Home Office","false","2017-08-04","<p>The latest published information on Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 can be found in Table 1202 of the “Fire and rescue authorities: operational statistics bulletin for England 2015 to 2016” available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables</a></p><p>Data for 2009-10 are published in Appendix table 15 accompanying the 2009-10 release here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fire-and-rescue-authorities-operational-statistics-bulletin-for-england-2009-to-2010" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fire-and-rescue-authorities-operational-statistics-bulletin-for-england-2009-to-2010</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","240 ; 241","2017-08-04T14:40:33.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731488/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731488/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731488/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-21","Fire Prevention: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, on how many occasions each fire safety authority brought prosecutions against persons under the Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731489","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-28","<p>Community benefit societies which are not registered charities currently pay corporation tax on their profits, investment income and any capital gains. At present the government does not consider a specific exemption from corporation tax to be appropriate as there are alternative routes by which community benefit societies could access an exemption- most importantly registering as a charity if the relevant conditions are met.</p><p> </p><p>The business rates system also includes a number of reliefs and exemptions for registered charities. If a community benefit society is a registered charity then it would be potentially eligible for this support. And all community benefit societies will benefit from the reduction in business rates announced at Budget 2016, which is worth almost £9bn.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-06-28T13:48:41.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731489/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731489/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731489/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-21","Community Interest Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the benefits of exempting registered community benefit societies from (a) corporation tax and (b) business and non-domestic rates.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731490","Department for Transport","false","2017-06-28","<p>The funding for schemes follows fiscal year cycles and accordingly spend is defined by year 2010/11 2011/12 etc.</p><p> </p><p>The historic spend figures for the A38 in Devon are as follows:</p><p>2010/11 - £2,985,863.17</p><p>2011/12 - £4,533,488.18</p><p>2012/13 - £3,999,018.54</p><p>2013/14 - £6,390,422.47</p><p>2014/15 - £20,452,939.65</p><p>2015/16 - £26,076,203.37</p><p>2016/17 - £9,129,144.01</p><p> </p><p>The peak in spend between 2014-2016 reflects the pinch point schemes which were delivered on the A38 within the Devon</p><p>In addition, annual routine maintenance such as grass cutting is funded from a separate maintenance budget and spend for this is excluded from the above figures.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-06-28T14:12:21.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731490/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731490/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731490/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-21","A38: Devon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much was spent on the A38 in Devon in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731491","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-28","<p>The Chancellor and other Treasury Ministers regularly meet with a range of businesses to inform policy development on a wide range of topics, including on how to increase productivity.</p><p>Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</a></p><p>On the specific issue of incentivising employees, the Government has asked Matthew Taylor to conduct an independent review of modern employment practices; this will include consideration of how employers can best inform and consult their workers.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-06-28T13:43:41.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731491/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731491/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731491/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-21","Productivity: Cooperatives","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with (a) the co-operative sector and (b) representatives from employee-owned businesses on increasing national productivity by incentivising and encouraging employees.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731492","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-06-26","<p>I have discussed the UN Human Rights Council with the US Ambassador to the UN, Nikki Haley, and stressed our appreciation for the US' contribution to the Council's work.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-06-26T13:02:53.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731492/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731492/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731492/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-06-21","USA: UN Human Rights Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterpart in the US on that country's membership of the UN Human Rights Council.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731493","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-06-26","<p>EDF’s planned date to start transmitting electricity to the national grid is 2025.</p><p> </p><p>If EDF does not start generating four years after 2025, then there will be reductions to the contract term; this means that for every day that Hinkley Point C (HPC) is late, the period of time where EDF gets increased certainty on the price of its electricity will be reduced. If HPC is not generating electricity by 2033, there is an option in the contract to cancel the contract.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-06-26T13:25:45.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731493/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731493/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731493/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-21","Hinkley Point C Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the planned date is for the Hinkley Point C reactor to start transmitting electricity to the National Grid; and whether the proposed contract for that reactor includes punitive measures for delay beyond that date.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731494","Department for International Trade","false","2017-06-29","<p>The value of trade in goods between Scotland and Israel was £120 million in 2016 (source: HM Revenue and Customs Regional Trade Statistics Database).</p><p>Israel is an important trading partner for the UK and we are committed to strengthening the trade relationship with Israel.</p><p>Israel currently has an Association Agreement with the EU on trade and we have established a UK-Israel working group to continue the progress we have seen to date, and to prepare the ground for a Post-Brexit trade agreement.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-06-29T11:13:01.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731494/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731494/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731494/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-06-21","Israel: Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps the Government is taking to increase trade between Scotland and Israel; and what potential opportunities there will be for that trading relationship after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Paul Masterton","East Renfrewshire","Paul Masterton","175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731495","Department for Transport","false","2017-06-28","<p>The funding for schemes follows fiscal year cycles and accordingly spend is defined by year 2017/18 2018/19 etc. Additionally, these figures are forecasts and as such they are not are sub divided by county boundaries at the current time.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Current forecast spend for the A38 within Devon and Cornwall is:</p><p>2017/18 - £17,367,440</p><p>2018/19 - £12,366,121</p><p>2019/20 - £11,900,162</p><p> </p><p>The forecast yearly spending figures for the A38 may be subject to change and regional prioritisation but could include schemes on bridge joint replacement, carriageway improvements and drainage works. This work is governed by a series of periodic checks and / or defined maintenance schedules.</p><p> </p><p>Annual routine maintenance, such as grass cutting, is funded from a separate budget and this is excluded from these figures.</p><p> </p><p>The funding settlement post 2020 is still being developed.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-06-28T14:24:09.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731495/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731495/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731495/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-21","A38: Devon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much funding has been allocated to the A38 in Devon in (a) 2018, (b) 2019, (c) 2020, (d) 2021 and (e) 2022.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731496","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-26","<p>The government has provided a guarantee for all European Structural and Investment Fund projects signed before the UK leaves the European Union (EU), providing they are value for money and in line with domestic priorities, including where those projects continue beyond the UK’s departure from the EU. The government’s manifesto committed to create a UK Shared Prosperity Fund. Further details on the Shared Prosperity Fund will be set out in due course.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","434","2017-06-26T15:08:59.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731496/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731496/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731496/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-21","EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if the Government will create a shared Prosperity Fund to replace EU economic aid.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731497","Wales Office","false","2017-07-03","<p>I visited the MOD St Athan site earlier this year and intend to do so again soon. My officials are in regular contact with MOD and Welsh Government officials on the relocation of the No. 4 School of Technical Training.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-07-03T16:05:36.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731497/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731497/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731497/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-06-21","MOD St Athan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, with reference to the Answer of 25 April 2017 to Question 70837, what plans are in place for officials or Ministers in his Department to visit the 4 School of Technical Training at MOD St Athan in 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731498","Home Office","false","2017-08-04","<p>The latest published information on Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 can be found in Table 1202 of the “Fire and rescue authorities: operational statistics bulletin for England 2015 to 2016” available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables</a></p><p>Data for 2009-10 are published in Appendix table 15 accompanying the 2009-10 release here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fire-and-rescue-authorities-operational-statistics-bulletin-for-england-2009-to-2010" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fire-and-rescue-authorities-operational-statistics-bulletin-for-england-2009-to-2010</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","178 ; 241","2017-08-04T14:40:33.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731498/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731498/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731498/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-21","Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) cautions, (b) Alteration Notices, (c) Enforcement Notices and (d) Prohibition Notices under Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 were issued by each Fire Safety Authority in England in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731499","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-06-27","<p>Yes, there is an ongoing assessment process as part of the proposed move of No. 4 School of Technical Training from Ministry of Defence St Athan to RAF Cosford, which examines the impact of the potential move on other units. For the current position, I refer the hon. Member to the answer given to her by my hon. Friend the then Minister for Defence Veterans, Reserves and Personnel (Mark Lancaster) on 24 April 2017 to Question 70832.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-06-27T15:40:07.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731499/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731499/answer","70832 - WQnA extract on MOD St Athan.pdf","70832 - WQnA extract on RAF St Athan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731499/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-06-21","RAF St Athan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 24 April 2017 to Question 70832, whether he has carried out an impact assessment of effect of relocation on (a) 614 RAF Auxiliary Squadron, (b) University of Wales Air Squadron, (c) 2300 Air Cadets Squadron, (d) Regional Rehabilitation Unit for Wales and the Midlands and (e) the Band of the Prince of Wales; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731500","Home Office","false","2017-08-04","<p>The latest published information on Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 can be found in Table 1202 of the “Fire and rescue authorities: operational statistics bulletin for England 2015 to 2016” available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables</a></p><p>Data for 2009-10 are published in Appendix table 15 accompanying the 2009-10 release here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fire-and-rescue-authorities-operational-statistics-bulletin-for-england-2009-to-2010" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fire-and-rescue-authorities-operational-statistics-bulletin-for-england-2009-to-2010</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","178 ; 240","2017-08-04T14:40:33.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731500/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731500/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731500/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-21","Fire Prevention: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many inspections of premises under the Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 were carried out by each Fire Safety Authority in England in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731501","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-06-27","<p>A detailed assessment of the future development at St Athan is on-going in order to make the site fit for purpose as one of our centres of mass for light infantry battalions which was announced in November 2016 in the estate optimisation strategy &quot;A Better Defence Estate&quot;. The Ministry of Defence will identify any requirement for the development of additional sports and recreation facilities as part of this assessment.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-06-27T15:09:32.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731501/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731501/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731501/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-06-21","RAF St Athan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 24 April 2017 to Question 70759, what plans are in place to expand existing sport and recreation facilities on his Department's St Athan site; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731502","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-06-27","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given to her by my hon. Friend the then Minister for Defence Veterans, Reserves and Personnel (Mark Lancaster) on 24 April 2017 to Question 70831.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-06-27T15:39:00.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731502/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731502/answer","20170424_WQnA_Extract_on_RAF_St_Athan[1]  HOC 70831.pdf","Hansard Extract 24 April 2017","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731502/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-06-21","RAF St Athan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 24 April 2017 to Question 70831, if he will place in the Library copies of discussion papers on the proposed relocation of his Department's St Athan No. 4 School of Technical Training to RAF Cosford; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731503","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-06-28","<p>We frequently raise a range of issues, including freedom of speech, with both Jordan and Saudi Arabia.</p><p>Ministers are also actively engaged on easing the tensions in the Gulf and calling for de-escalation. Regional unity is crucial for the long-term stability of the Middle East.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-06-28T14:19:18.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731503/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731503/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731503/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-06-21","Arab States: al-Jazeera Satellite Television","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his counterparts in (a) Jordan and (b) Saudi Arabia on the revocation of licences for the Al Jazeera Media Network to broadcast in those countries.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731504","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-06-27","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given to her by my hon. Friend the then Minister for Defence Veterans, Reserves and Personnel (Mark Lancaster) on 24 April 2017 to Question 70755.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-06-27T15:46:16.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731504/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731504/answer","20170424_WQnA_extract_on_MOD_Procurement.pdf","70755 - WQnA extract on MOD Procurement","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731504/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-06-21","Ministry of Defence: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 24 April 2017 to Question 70755, if he will place the 2017 Initial Gate Business Case for Project CUBIT in the Library; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731505","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-06-28","<p>In my meetings with the Deputy Foreign Minister from the United Arab Emirates and my counterparts from the region, I have made it clear that we want de-escalation.</p><p>In the meantime, we have updated our travel advice to alert British nationals to the recent announcement that showing sympathy for Qatar on social media or by any other means of communication is an offence in the UAE.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-06-28T14:21:10.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731505/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731505/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731505/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-06-21","United Arab Emirates: Freedom of Expression","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his counterpart in the UAE on the recent announcement of that country's intention to punish expressions of sympathy towards Qatar with imprisonment for up to 15 years.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731506","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-06-28","<p>We are aware that air carriers registered in Qatar, including Qatar Airways, have restrictions on the airspace they can use. There are currently no direct flights between Qatar and a number of countries, including Bahrain, United Arab Emirates and Saudi Arabia.</p><p>We understand that alternative routes are being used for commercial shipping to and from Qatar.</p><p>We continue to monitor the situation closely and will continue to assess the impact of restrictions as the dispute continues.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2017-06-28T14:12:27.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731506/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731506/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731506/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-06-21","Qatar: International Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect of sanctions imposed by other countries on Qatar since 5 June 2017 on (a) commercial flights and (b) commercial shipping between the UK and Qatar.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731507","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-27","<p>The previous Financial Secretary, in a letter to the hon. Member for Bassetlaw dated 19<sup>th</sup> April 2017, set out that a waiver of landfill tax for such cases would set a perverse incentive which may lead to the abandonment of other such waste sites. Therefore it would be counterproductive to waive the landfill tax liability in this case. I agree with this assessment.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury has made no estimate as to the value of the site at Sandy Lane, Worksop.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury has not held any meetings with other government departments concerning the removal of landfill tax from abandoned waste sites owned by the Crown Estate.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","599 ; 877","2017-06-27T15:13:19.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731507/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731507/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731507/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-21","Landfill Tax: Worksop","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the merits of the proposal by the hon. Member for Bassetlaw on the removal of landfill taxes to assist the removal of waste from the abandoned waste site at Sandy Lane, Worksop.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731508","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Electoral Commission collected data from Returning Officers for all UK constituencies following the UK Parliamentary General Election on 7 May 2015. The data shows that an estimated 12,803 people tried to vote on polling day and were unregistered.</p><p>This number is based on data from 418 constituencies, as not all Returning Officers provided data and of those that did, some of the data provided was approximate. Figures for each constituency are available on the Electoral Commission’s website at <a href="http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/excel_doc/0011/191648/UKPGE-turnout-postal-rejected-admin-amended-WEB.xlsx" target="_blank">http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/excel_doc/0011/191648/UKPGE-turnout-postal-rejected-admin-amended-WEB.xlsx</a></p>","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson",,"2017-07-17T16:07:01.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731508/answer","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731508/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731508/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2017-06-21","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, how many instances of voters being wrongly excluded from the electoral list were identified at the 2015 General Election; and in which constituencies such exclusions took place.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731509","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-06-28","<p>As the Government manifesto outlines, we will continue to invest a record £2.5 billion over six years to better protect the country from flooding. This includes over 1,500 flood defence schemes, which will better protect more than 300,000 properties by 2021.</p><p> </p><p>From April 2015 until May 2017, this investment has given better protection to 97,000 homes. This has been achieved by £785 million of Government grants in aid and £179 million of external contributions.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-06-28T16:07:28.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731509/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731509/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731509/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-06-21","Flood Control: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent progress his Department has made on investment in flood defences.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731510","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-06","<p>The Coroner’s report into Lakanal House recommended simplifying the fire safety guidance relating to Building Regulations (Approved Document B). This work was being progressed.</p><p>Following the tragedy at Grenfell Tower, we will need to consider the position on guidance further alongside the Prime Minister’s commitment to look at wider issues. This work will now need to be informed by any recommendations that the independent inquiry into the Grenfell Tower fire makes.</p><p>In the interim, we have set up an expert panel to advise us on any immediate steps that should be taken to ensure fire safety. The role of the expert panel and the advice already given following Grenfell is set out in a note published last week at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/explanatory-note-on-safety-checks-and-testing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/explanatory-note-on-safety-checks-and-testing</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-06T14:54:27.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731510/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731510/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731510/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-21","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if the Government will review fire safety regulations to ensure that highrise accommodation is required to have more than one fire exit.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731511","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-06","<p>The Coroner’s report into Lakanal House recommended simplifying the fire safety guidance relating to Building Regulations (Approved Document B). This work was being progressed.</p><p>Following the tragedy at Grenfell Tower, we will need to consider the position on guidance further alongside the Prime Minister’s commitment to look at wider issues. This work will now need to be informed by any recommendations that the independent inquiry into the Grenfell Tower fire makes.</p><p>In the interim, we have set up an expert panel to advise us on any immediate steps that should be taken to ensure fire safety. The role of the expert panel and the advice already given following Grenfell is set out in a note published last week at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/explanatory-note-on-safety-checks-and-testing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/explanatory-note-on-safety-checks-and-testing</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-06T14:57:27.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731511/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731511/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731511/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-21","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if the Government will review fire safety regulations to ensure that cladding on highrise accommodation is fireproof.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731513","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-24","<p>Building regulation guidance provides that newly built high rise accommodation, over 30 metres, is constructed with a sprinkler system.</p><p>The Department wrote to all social housing providers in 2013 following the recommendations in a Coroner’s report into firefighter deaths which occurred at Shirley Towers in Southampton in April 2010. That letter encouraged providers to consider the retrofitting of sprinklers in older residential tower blocks. The Department then reinforced the content of that letter in its response to the Coroner’s report into the Lakanal House Fire – a copy of which can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/205567/Annex_B_-_SoS_DCLG_Rule_43_response.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/205567/Annex_B_-_SoS_DCLG_Rule_43_response.pdf</a></p><p>An independent expert panel has been set up to provide advice to the Government on any immediate measures needed to make buildings safe following the Grenfell Tower fire. The panel will be led by Sir Ken Knight, former London Fire Commissioner and former Government Chief Fire and Rescue Adviser. It will consider safety measures, policies, inspection and regulation, taking account of both the Grenfell Tower fire and ongoing fire safety inspections. It will look at any immediate action required to ensure public confidence that everything possible is being done to make all public and private buildings safe as quickly as possible.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-24T15:30:53.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731513/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731513/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731513/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-21","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if the Government will review the fire safety regulations to ensure that highrise accommodation is required to have sprinklers.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731514","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-26","<p>As of 22 June 2017, the Tax-Free Childcare helpline has answered over 80,000 phone calls from parents and over 40,000 calls from childcare providers. The average call response time is 4 seconds.</p><p>As of 22 June 2017 almost 50,000 parents had successfully applied for Tax-Free Childcare and over 40,000 childcare providers had signed up.</p><p> </p><p>At Budget 2017, the Office for Budget Responsibility forecast that there would be 790,000 families using TFC by the end of 2017/18.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","222 ; 223 ; 224 ; 228","2017-06-26T15:23:36.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731514/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731514/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731514/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-21","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the average call response time was to calls made to the Tax-Free Childcare helpline in (a) May and (b) June 2017.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731515","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-06-30","<p>My predecessor as Minister for Civil Society appointed Steve Holliday as the Chair of the independent review of full-time social action by young people on 13 March 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Progress with the review was delayed for six weeks due to Purdah, and we will agree a revised process and timetable with the Chair in the coming weeks. We anticipate that the review will be completed by December 2017.</p><p><strong></strong><br><br></p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","190","2017-06-30T15:43:28.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731515/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731515/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731515/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-21","Youth Social Action Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether it is planned that the Youth Full-Time Social Action review will publish its findings and recommendations by October 2017.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731516","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-06-30","<p>No Community Rehabilitation Company (CRC) is in formal dispute with the department. We have undertaken an overarching review of probation, looking at the standards we set for providers and how we hold them to account. We have already made some changes to how CRCs are paid so they can focus on activities that best rehabilitate offenders and keep society safe. The details of these negotiations are commercially sensitive.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-06-30T13:37:52.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731516/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731516/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731516/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-21","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many community rehabilitation companies are in dispute with his Department on the payment mechanism.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731517","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-06-26","<p>Clean growth is a key pillar of our industrial strategy. The low carbon sector already brings significant benefits to the UK, employing over 230,000 people directly and another 200,000 through supply chains. Within the sector, the UK has established world-leading expertise in several areas of green technology, including offshore wind and electric vehicles. Since 2012, over £56 billion has been invested in renewable energy generation in the UK. In 2016, one in five battery electric cars sold in the EU was made in the UK.</p><p>Certainty for the UK’s energy policy is provided by several frameworks, including the Climate Change Act 2008. This established the UK’s 2050 target to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by at least 80% on 1990 levels and a supporting framework of five year carbon budgets.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-06-26T15:21:02.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731517/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731517/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731517/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-21","Foreign Investment in UK: Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans the Government has to provide certainty of energy policy in order to attract green technology companies to the UK.","false","Biography information for John McNally","Falkirk","John McNally","226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731518","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-06-26","<p>This Government is committed to tackling climate change and to the UK’s Climate Change Act. On average, Government policies reduce household energy bills because energy efficiency measures mean that less energy is used, more than offsetting the costs other policies add to energy bills.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-06-26T15:21:36.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731518/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731518/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731518/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-21","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government plans to take to ensure that reductions in energy bills do not affect commitments to emissions reductions.","false","Biography information for John McNally","Falkirk","John McNally","227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731519","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-06-30","<p>This information is commercially sensitive.</p><p> </p><p>We hold providers rigorously to account for their performance and take action wherever they are falling short. Our contract management teams closely monitor and robustly manage providers to make sure they fulfil their contractual commitments to maintain service delivery, reduce reoffending, protect the public and provide value for money to the taxpayer. If standards are not met, financial penalties can be applied through Service Credits. Service Credits are a payment made by the Community Rehabilitation Company (CRC) back to the Government, as a means of compensating for services under the contract where the CRC fails to meet the contractual service levels expected.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-06-30T13:39:36.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731519/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731519/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731519/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-21","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many financial penalties have been incurred by (a) number and (b) financial value by community rehabilitation companies in (i) England, (ii) Wales and (iii) each county in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731520","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-26","<p>As of 22 June 2017, the Tax-Free Childcare helpline has answered over 80,000 phone calls from parents and over 40,000 calls from childcare providers. The average call response time is 4 seconds.</p><p>As of 22 June 2017 almost 50,000 parents had successfully applied for Tax-Free Childcare and over 40,000 childcare providers had signed up.</p><p> </p><p>At Budget 2017, the Office for Budget Responsibility forecast that there would be 790,000 families using TFC by the end of 2017/18.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","222 ; 223 ; 224 ; 225","2017-06-26T15:23:36.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731520/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731520/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731520/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-21","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many parents have signed up for the Tax-Free Childcare scheme to date.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731521","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-06-30","<p>We have been carrying out a comprehensive review of the probation system to improve outcomes for offenders and communities while making sure public protection remains our top priority. It considered all aspects of the probation system, including CRC performance and contractual arrangements. The review has now concluded and we will be publishing our findings in due course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-06-30T13:41:11.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731521/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731521/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731521/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-21","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when his Department expects the review of community rehabilitation company performance measures to be completed.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731522","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-06-30","<p>Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) came into existence on 1 June 2014 and ownership was transferred to new rehabilitation providers on 1 February 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The performance of CRCs, including compliance with Licence and Post-Sentence Supervision (PSS), is assessed through a range of service levels and through a robust contract management and assurance process. Performance information against these service levels is published quarterly, and the latest data can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/community-performance-quarterly-mi-update-to-december-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/community-performance-quarterly-mi-update-to-december-2016</a>. End state targets for some service levels were only expected to be met by February 2017, and this period is due for publication on 27 July 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Public protection is our top priority and we will take all necessary action to make sure the probation system is reducing reoffending and preventing future victims. We have undertaken an overarching review of probation, looking at the standards we set for providers and how we hold them to account and will be publishing our findings in due course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","517","2017-06-30T13:43:40.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731522/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731522/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731522/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-21","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many end-state performance targets have been met by each community rehabilitation company providers in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731523","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-06-30","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Community Rehabilitation Companies came into existence on 1 June 2014 and ownership was transferred to new rehabilitation providers on 1 February 2015. We have since undertaken an overarching review of probation, looking at the standards we set for providers and how we hold them to account and will be publishing our findings in due course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","519","2017-06-30T13:35:54.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731523/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731523/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731523/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-21","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many appointments have been (a) offered and (b) undertaken by service users of community rehabilitation companies in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731524","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Electoral Commission collected data from Returning Officers for all UK constituencies following the UK Parliamentary general election on 7 May 2015. The numbers of postal vote statements rejected by Returning Officers due to mismatched signatures and mismatched dates of birth were as follows:</p><p>Postal Vote statements rejected due to mismatched signatures: 46,840</p><ul><li>Postal Vote statements rejected due to mismatched dates of birth: 38,148</li><li>Postal Vote statements rejected due to mismatched both dates of birth and signatures: 16,912</li></ul><p>Figures for each constituency are available on the Electoral Commission’s website at <a href="http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/excel_doc/0011/191648/UKPGE-turnout-postal-rejected-admin-amended-WEB.xlsx" target="_blank">http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/excel_doc/0011/191648/UKPGE-turnout-postal-rejected-admin-amended-WEB.xlsx</a></p><p>The Electoral Commission is currently collecting data from Returning Officers in relation to the 2017 general election, which will include the number of rejected postal votes. The Commission will publish this in the autumn.</p>","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson",,"2017-07-17T16:04:32.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731524/answer","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731524/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731524/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2017-06-21","Absent Voting","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, how many postal votes were discounted because the signature or date of birth was not accepted by returning officers in each constituency in the (a) 2015 and (b) 2017 General Election.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731525","Department for Transport","false","2017-06-26","<p>Prior to the re-launch of the Franchising Programme in spring 2013, the costs of different franchising projects were not individually recorded. Figures from April 2013 are as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Cost (£M)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>9.461</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>8.544</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>14.620</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>12.652</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>These figures include adviser costs (financial, technical and legal advisers) and VAT where applicable.</p><p> </p><p>The costs of procuring the current Intercity East Coast franchise (awarded 2015) were not charged to the public purse and are not included in the above figures (these costs were covered by the Performance Bond that National Express put forward following its default of the previous East Coast contract).</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Note that the sums invested in each re-franchising project are dwarfed by the (Resource) Support for Passenger Rail Services benefits to the Department from the re-franchising.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-06-26T15:31:46.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731525/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731525/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731525/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-21","Railways: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the total external costs of advisers and other bought-in items was to his Department for franchise specification and procurement for each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731526","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-06-28","<p>The Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport wrote to the Welsh Minister for Lifelong Learning and Welsh Language on 27th February 2017 seeking agreement on the preferred candidate, in accordance with Clause 23 (9) of the BBC Charter. The preferred candidate was found to be above the line by the panel, which included the Welsh Government representative.</p><p>On 28th February 2017, the Welsh Minister for Lifelong Learning and Welsh Language sent a letter to the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport stating that the Welsh Government was unable to endorse the preferred candidate.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-06-28T14:03:52.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731526/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731526/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731526/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-21","BBC Board: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, for what reasons she did not appoint one of the above the line candidates for the role of representing Wales on the BBC Board.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731527","Department of Health","false","2017-06-26","<p>NHS England (London’s) mental health response to the Grenfell Tower Fire has been a stepped approach which is designed to enable people affected to return to normal life as early as possible using existing support mechanisms. We are committed to ensuring that the right support is available at every stage.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-06-26T16:14:01.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731527/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731527/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731527/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proactive steps (a) his Department and (b) NHS England are taking to ensure adequate provision of mental health support for people affected by the Grenfell Tower fire.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731528","Department of Health","false","2017-06-26","<p>NHS England (London) is working with Professor Chris Brewin, professor of clinical psychology at University College London who worked extensively with people suffering Post Traumatic Stress Disorder following the 7/7 incidents.</p><p> </p><p>In the first days of a major incident the focus is on providing support to enable people to talk about their experience and their fears and to help them to feel safe. NHS England (London) will be assessing exact numbers when we have accurate figures on the numbers of people affected.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-06-26T13:25:15.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731528/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731528/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731528/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the number of (a) adults and (b) children who are (i) experiencing or (ii) likely to experience post-traumatic stress disorder, depression or other mental health problems as a result of the Grenfell Tower fire.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731529","Department for Education","false","2017-07-03","<p>Delivering enough school places is one of the government’s top priorities and the free schools programme is part of delivering this. Thanks to our reforms there are 1.8 million more children in schools rated good or outstanding than in 2010. Over 50 new schools are expected to open in September 2017. There are currently over 350 further schools in the pipeline that will create over 150,000 places when the schools reach capacity.</p><p> </p><p>We have already committed £5.8bn for local authorities up to 2020 to deliver new school places, on top of our investment in the free schools programme.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-07-03T16:05:30.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731529/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731529/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731529/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Free Schools: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on the number of free schools to be built each year.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731530","Department of Health","false","2017-06-26","<p>NHS England (London) is working with the local clinical commissioning group and provider to make sure any necessary support is provided.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-06-26T16:16:26.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731530/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731530/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731530/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if his Department will allocate additional funding to the local mental health trust to strengthen provision of mental health support for people affected by the Grenfell Tower fire.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731531","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>We want every pupil to have the opportunity to attend a good school and will provide more details in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-06-29T16:15:54.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731531/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731531/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731531/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Schools: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on preventing new places in schools that have been rated inadequate or requiring improvement by Ofsted.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731532","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-06-26","<p><br>I refer the rt Hon Member to the answers today to Questions UIN 441 and UIN 443.</p><p>Other support announced by the Government includes a £5 million Grenfell Tower Residents’ Discretionary Fund to help pay for the immediate financial needs of those affected, which we will keep under review</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-06-26T16:47:24.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731532/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731532/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731532/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-21","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if his Department will allocate additional funding to the relevant local authority to support the mental health of people affected by the Grenfell Tower fire.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731533","Department of Health","false","2017-06-26","<p>The Local Authority is responsible for allocating a lead social care worker to the bereaved. Every Grenfell Tower resident has been allocated a key worker to provide wrap around care. Cruse bereavement support, a leading national charity, is also available for the bereaved.</p><p> </p><p>To co-ordinate the local response a central command centre was set up by government on 16th June, led by the chief executive of the City of London Corporation and the chief executive of the London Borough of Southwark Council.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-06-26T16:09:50.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731533/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731533/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731533/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what specific steps his Department is taking to support the mental health of people who have experienced bereavement as a result of the Grenfell Tower fire.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731534","Department for Education","false","2017-06-27","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answers I provided on 27/06/2017 to Question number 713 and 714.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening","458","2017-06-27T13:21:54.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731534/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731534/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731534/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Schools: Sponsorship","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on the involvement of universities in academy sponsorship, the founding of free schools and charging maximum tuition fees.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731535","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-06-30","<p>Ministers regularly meet representatives of EU funding bodies for a wide range of discussions.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-06-30T13:36:22.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731535/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731535/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731535/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-21","Culture: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with representatives of the relevant EU funding bodies on applications for EU funding by UK creative organisations for multi-annual projects running until 2020.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731536","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-06-30","<p>The Secretary of State meets regularly with industry on a range of issues in relation to the UK leaving the European Union (EU). The European Convention on Cinematographic Co-Production is a Council of Europe (CoE) convention and is not part of EU law and will therefore not be be affected by the UK’s decision to leave the EU.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-06-30T11:40:03.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731536/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731536/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731536/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-21","Film","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions she has had with industry representatives on the effect of the UK exiting the EU on cross-border co-production agreements.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731537","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-06-28","<p>The Government has made no such assessment. Like other licensing schemes run in the UK, the collection of artist’s resale right is managed by collective management organisations on behalf of artists. These organisations, which include DACS and the Artist’s Collecting Society, are mandated by artists to collect on their behalf, and are responsible for publishing information on artist income generated from the resale right.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-06-28T12:35:48.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731537/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731537/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731537/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-21","Arts: Income","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent assessment he has made of the trends in income from artists resale rights.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731538","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-06-30","<p>The borrowing and lending of objects with European partners and touring of exhibitions and performances is an important part of a thriving arts and cultural sector. We are working with Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs, Border Force, and organisations in the arts and museums sectors who regularly transport cultural objects to understand the current operating environment and what systems may need to be maintained or introduced. We want to have a new customs arrangement that continues to ensure cross-border movements are as smooth and frictionless as possible.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-06-30T13:30:23.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731538/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731538/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731538/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-21","Museums and Galleries: Collections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment she has made of the effect of the UK exiting the customs union on the procedures for transporting cultural objects between museums across international borders.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731539","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>The government would like to open more maths schools across England. Kings College London Mathematics School and Exeter Mathematics School are proving highly successful. Both are rated outstanding by Ofsted and were well above average for post 16 progress in 2016.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-06-29T16:49:13.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731539/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731539/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731539/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Schools: Mathematics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on the opening of specialist maths schools.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731540","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-06-30","<p>Leaving the EU means we can take our own decisions about how to deliver the policy objectives previously targeted by EU funding. We are discussing closely with stakeholders all EU funding schemes in the round, to ensure that any ongoing funding commitments best serve the UK‘s national interest.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-06-30T11:42:55.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731540/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731540/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731540/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-21","Culture: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether an assessment has been made of the merits of continuing to pay into and receive funding from Creative Europe after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731541","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>Schools play a vital role in promoting integration and promoting an understanding of different faiths and communities. We expect all schools to be inclusive and respect the protected characteristics of their pupils in line with their responsibilities under the Equality Act 2010. Schools designated with a religious character have the freedom to take faith into account when allocating places. We will continue to work closely with faith schools to promote and support integration and will set out further details in due course.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2017-06-29T16:44:52.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731541/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731541/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731541/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Faith Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on inclusivity rules and faith school admissions.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731542","Department for Education","false","2017-06-27","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answers I provided on 27/06/2017 to Question number 713 and 714.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening","455","2017-06-27T13:21:54.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731542/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731542/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731542/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Schools: Sponsorship","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on the number of independent schools involved in academy sponsorship or the founding of free schools","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731543","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-28","<p>The tax treatment for independent schools varies depending on whether or not they have charity status. In common with other organisations, independent schools must abide by [EU and UK] tax rules and pay all tax that is due.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-06-28T13:47:23.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731543/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731543/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731543/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-21","Taxation: Private Education","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his policy is on the tax status of independent schools.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731544","Department for Education","false","2017-06-27","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I provided on 27/06/2017 to Question number 128.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2017-06-27T12:50:18.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731544/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731544/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731544/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Grammar Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on the ban on the establishment of new selective schools.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731545","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>We want every pupil to be able to access a good school place. That is why we routinely keep the admissions system under review.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-06-29T16:13:53.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731545/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731545/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731545/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans to carry out a review of school admissions policy.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731546","Department for Education","false","2017-06-30","<p>The Early Years Foundation Stage (EYFS) statutory framework sets the standards that all early years providers must meet to ensure that children learn and develop well and are kept healthy and safe. The EYFS can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/early-years-foundation-stage-framework--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/early-years-foundation-stage-framework--2</a>.</p><p>For literacy, the EYFS requires early years practitioners to encourage children to link sounds and letters, through the use of phonics, and to begin to read and write. Children must be given access to a wide range of reading materials (books, poems, and other written materials) to ignite their interest. For teaching numeracy, practitioners provide children with opportunities to develop and improve their skills in counting, understanding and using numbers, calculating simple addition and subtraction problems; and to describe shapes, spaces, and measure</p><p>Through the recent primary assessment consultation, we are exploring the content of the early learning goals (ELGs) specified in the EYFS, including those relating to literacy and numeracy. The consultation closed on 22 June, and a Government response will be issued in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-06-30T13:57:45.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731546/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731546/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731546/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Pre-school Education: Basic Skills","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on the teaching of literacy and numeracy in the early years.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731547","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>It is vital that pupils learn to read in the early years of primary school.</p><p> </p><p>There is a substantial body of evidence which demonstrates that systematic synthetic phonics is the most effective method for teaching all pupils to read. The phonics screening check for pupils in year 1 was introduced nationally in 2012, to make sure that pupils have learned phonic decoding to an age appropriate standard. Thanks to the hard work of teachers, our continued focus on raising standards and the increased emphasis on phonics‎, there are now an additional 147,000 six-year-olds on track to becoming fluent readers. Given this success, we continue to support the administration of the phonics screening check in our primary schools.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-06-29T16:47:40.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731547/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731547/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731547/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Literacy: Teaching Methods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on phonics screening testing.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731548","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>Multiplication tables provide an important underpinning to gaining greater mathematical knowledge and improving pupils’ written and mental arithmetic. The requirement to teach multiplication tables is included in the mathematics National Curriculum. We expect that all pupils should be able to recall and use facts for multiplication tables, up to 12, by the end of Year 4.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-06-29T16:33:31.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731548/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731548/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731548/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Mathematics: Primary Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on the knowledge of times tables by 11 year olds.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731549","Department for Education","false","2017-07-06","<p>Our ambition for a world-class technical education system in England must be underpinned by high-quality teaching and leadership in the Further Education sector. We want to encourage experienced experts to bring their up-to-date industry-standard skills into the Further Education sector to enhance the quality of technical education. We are looking at ways in which we can develop more effective relationships between industry and the FE sector, and we expect to announce further detail in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-06T16:55:24.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731549/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731549/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731549/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Further Education: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on the creation of a new national programme to attract experienced industry professionals to work in further education colleges.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731550","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>Key Stage 3 is a vital part of secondary education. The Government is clear that all pupils deserve to receive a broad and balanced curriculum in the first three years of secondary school.</p><p> </p><p>All secondary schools are held to account on the basis of their results at the end of Key Stage 4. Ofsted’s school inspection handbook makes clear that inspectors will consider the progress that pupils are making at the end of each year and each Key Stage.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is considering how best to improve accountability at Key Stage 3.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","806","2017-06-29T15:58:12.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731550/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731550/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731550/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Secondary Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on accountability of schools at key stage 3.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731551","Department for Education","false","2017-07-06","<p>As part of our Industrial Strategy, we will deliver on our plans for new Institutes of Technology. These will enable more young people to take advanced technical qualifications, and become key institutions for the development of the skills required by local, national and regional industry. Further details will be published in due course.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-06T16:42:33.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731551/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731551/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731551/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Institutes of Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on the introduction of new institutes of technology.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731552","Department for Education","false","2017-07-06","<p>Further detail on the manifesto commitment to look at the funding of further, technical and higher education will be provided in due course.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","803","2017-07-06T16:58:45.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731552/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731552/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731552/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Further Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on reviewing funding across tertiary education.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731553","Department for Education","false","2017-06-30","<p>The government is committed to delivering 3 million apprenticeship starts by 2020. Apprenticeship reforms continue to improve the quality of apprenticeships for all, providing the skills that employers need. Our reforms include implementation of the Apprenticeship Levy and new funding system to encourage employers to offer more high quality apprenticeships opportunities to people of all ages.</p><p> </p><p>There were 509,400 apprenticeship starts in the 2015/16 academic year of which 285,300 were by people under 25. Our ‘Get In Go Far’ campaign aims to encourage more young people to apply and more employers to offer opportunities.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-06-30T13:46:45.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731553/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731553/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731553/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on the number of apprenticeships for young people to be delivered by 2020.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731554","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>The Government believes that the English Baccalaureate (EBacc) provides the right educational foundation for the majority of pupils. We want to see a significant increase in the proportion of pupils in mainstream secondary schools entering the EBacc combination of subjects at GCSE.</p><p> </p><p>We will publish further detail about the EBacc policy in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","467","2017-06-29T16:20:33.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731554/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731554/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731554/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","English Baccalaureate: GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on the proportion of pupils to be entered for the EBacc combination of GCSEs by the end of this Parliament.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731555","Department for Education","false","2017-06-30","<p>From April 2018, we plan to allow levy-paying employers to transfer up to 10% of the annual value of funds entering their apprenticeship service accounts to another employer or apprenticeship training agency.</p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-06-30T14:50:41.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731555/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731555/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731555/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on allowing large firms to place apprentices within their supply chains.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731556","Department for Education","false","2017-07-06","<p>Apprenticeships provide an excellent opportunity for individuals wishing to combine paid work with on and off the job training, and should play a key role for people entering professions – including teaching. A group of schools, led by Sir Andrew Carter, is therefore developing a postgraduate teacher apprenticeship, which will offer trainees high-quality, employment-based training and support schools to recoup their apprenticeship levy payments. We expect the route will be available from September 2018 and will confirm further details of this new route in due course.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-06T16:44:13.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731556/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731556/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731556/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Teachers: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on teaching apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731557","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>The Government believes that the English Baccalaureate (EBacc) provides the right educational foundation for the majority of pupils. We want to see a significant increase in the proportion of pupils in mainstream secondary schools entering the EBacc combination of subjects at GCSE.</p><p> </p><p>We will publish further detail about the EBacc policy in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","466","2017-06-29T16:20:33.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731557/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731557/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731557/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","English Baccalaureate: GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on the proportion of schools to be entered for the Ebacc combination of GCSEs by 2025.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731558","Department for Education","false","2017-07-04","<p>My Department wants to make sure that English technical education rivals the best in the world.</p><p>My Department is exploring policy options that enable technical education students to receive clear information and gives them better support throughout the application process. This will make it easier for students to compare technical and academic options</p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-04T12:38:18.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731558/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731558/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731558/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Vocational Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on introducing a UCAS-style portal for technical education.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731559","Department for Transport","false","2017-06-29","<p>The Government is implementing apprenticeship reforms to continue to improve the quality of apprenticeships for all, providing the skills that employers need to reach our commitment of 3 million starts in England by 2020. The Government has also expressed a desire that it does not want the costs of travel to deter young people, and so the Department (in discussion with the Department for Education) has started exploring options for travel for apprentices.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-06-29T10:16:36.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731559/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731559/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731559/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-21","Public Transport: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his policy is on bus and train travel for apprentices.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731560","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>The Government is committed to improving educational standards for all pupils, regardless of their background. That is why we have introduced a broad, knowledge based, academic, and high quality curriculum, which covers the core academic subjects, and provides a rich arts education giving pupils a deeper appreciation of culture.</p><p> </p><p>In 2014, the Government introduced a new, more ambitious National Curriculum based on this knowledge based approach and is funding programmes such as Maths Hubs and Science Learning Partnerships to support schools to teach it.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","799","2017-06-29T16:00:43.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731560/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731560/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731560/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Curriculum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on access to an academic, knowledge-rich curriculum.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731561","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-06-27","<p>The Government is committed to testing ambitious new approaches to career learning and training for people in work and returning to work, as announced in the Budget. More detailed proposals will be set out in due course.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-06-27T14:41:28.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731561/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731561/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731561/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-21","Training: Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his policy is on leave for training for all employees.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731562","Department for Education","false","2017-07-06","<p>The Government wants to test ambitious new approaches to career learning, as announced at the Budget. Detailed proposals for implementing the Manifesto commitment to establish a national retraining scheme will be set out in due course.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-06T16:53:20.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731562/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731562/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731562/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on the introduction of a national retraining scheme.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731563","Department for Education","true","2017-07-03","<p><del class="ministerial">The Government is committed to building a stronger and more prosperous Britain for all. Developing an appropriate degree apprenticeship, that protects the professional status of teaching, will be an effective way of upskilling those individuals with a passion for teaching, such as teaching assistants. We will work with the sector in progressing this work, with employers at the heart of the route’s development.</del></p><p> </p><p><ins class="ministerial">The Government is developing an appropriate degree apprenticeship, that protects the professional status of teaching and will be an effective way of upskilling those individuals with a passion for teaching, such as teaching assistants. We will work with the sector in progressing this work, with employers at the heart of the route’s development.</ins></p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-03T15:26:55.323Z","2017-07-04T14:59:05.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731563/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731563/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731563/answer","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731563/answer/previousversion/1340","Biography information for Anne Milton","60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Classroom Assistants: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on teaching assistants becoming qualified teachers through a degree apprenticeship.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731564","Department for Education","false","2017-07-10","<p>The government wants people aged 19 and over in England, who lack core digital skills, to be able to access specified basic digital skills training free of charge, where it is made available by providers as part of publicly funded adult education.</p><p>This will enable adults to secure the basic digital skills they need to operate effectively in day-to-day life.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-10T17:01:10.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731564/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731564/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731564/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Digital Technology: Lifelong Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on lifelong learning in digital skills.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731565","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-06-30","<p>As with all EU funds, we are carefully considering the impact and effectiveness of the investments made through Creative Europe. International cooperation is integral to maintaining our world class creative industries sector, and we will ensure that they are able to continue to cooperate with international partners after we exit the EU.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-06-30T12:19:40.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731565/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731565/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731565/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-21","Culture: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment she has made of the effectiveness of Creative Europe in facilitating international professional networks for the creative industries over the last five years.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731566","Department for Education","false","2017-06-30","<p>We know that high-quality childcare is important not just for working parents but also for a child’s development and school readiness. We will provide more details on our plans in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","499","2017-06-30T13:06:02.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731566/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731566/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731566/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Primary Education: Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on funding the creation of nurseries in primary schools.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731567","Department for Education","false","2017-06-30","<p>We know that high-quality childcare is important not just for working parents but also for a child’s development and school readiness. We will provide more details on our plans in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","498","2017-06-30T13:06:02.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731567/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731567/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731567/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Primary Education: Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on all new primary schools including a nursery.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731568","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-06-30","<p>Leaving the EU means we can take our own decisions about how to deliver the policy objectives previously targeted by EU funding. We are consulting closely with stakeholders to review all EU funding schemes in the round, to ensure that any ongoing funding commitments best serve the UK‘s national interest.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-06-30T11:45:17.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731568/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731568/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731568/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-21","Arts: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she has taken to collect data on the (a) amount and (b) proportion of the UK's allocation of the European Structural Investment Fund that have benefited the arts and culture sector.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731569","Department of Health","false","2017-06-26","<p>We are committed to offering Youth Mental Health First Aid training to a teacher in every secondary school by 2019 and to reach 1,000 schools by the end of 2017. The Government’s manifesto includes a commitment to offer this training to all schools, including primary schools.</p><p> </p><p>We have made £200,000 available in 2017/18 to train the first 1,000 teachers in 2017 and we will work with Mental Health First Aid England to agree funding for future years.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","660","2017-06-26T13:19:07.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731569/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731569/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731569/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-21","Teachers: First Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what his policy is on mental health first aid training for teachers.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731570","Department for Education","false","2017-07-04","<p>Good mental health is a priority for the Department. Mental health issues can have a profound impact on the whole of a child’s life, including their attainment. Schools can play an important role in promoting mental wellbeing and supporting pupils, but teachers are not mental health professionals and knowledge and practice in the mental health field is constantly developing. Action taken by them is best supported by advice from specialist services, as well as by access to treatment for pupils where needed. We are investing an additional £1.4 billion in children’s mental health services in the five years to 2020.</p><p>Our schools/Child and Adolescent Mental Health Services (CAMHS) link joint training pilot, across 225 schools in 27 Clinical Commissioning Groups, identified a range of different models for schools working more closely with single points of contact in specialist mental health services – making use of the additional investment. These resulted in a strengthening of communication and joint working arrangements between schools and specialist services, with quantifiable improvements in understanding of the referral routes amongst school staff – leading in many cases to higher quality and more timely referrals.</p><p>We will be considering with the Department of Health how best to build on the results of this pilot to improve links between schools, colleges and NHS mental health services as a part of our joint children and young people’s mental health green paper, to be published by the end of the year. We will look at any funding requirements in that context.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","661","2017-07-04T16:45:34.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731570/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731570/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731570/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Schools: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on ensuring that every school has a single point of contact for mental health services.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731571","Department for Education","false","2017-06-30","<p>Under the Children and Young Persons Act 2008, there is a duty on all Secretaries of State, but in practice primarily on the Secretary of State for Education, to promote the wellbeing of all children in England.</p><p>Under the Children Act 1989, local authorities have a duty to safeguard and promote the welfare of all children in their area, including a duty to provide services for children in need. Local authorities are responsible for the delivery and quality of children’s services in their area.</p><p>Central government formally intervenes where local government demonstrably fails to deliver, such as when Ofsted has judged services as inadequate. The Department’s approach to intervention, and to delivering our vision for excellent children’s social care more widely, is set out in ‘<em>Putting Children First</em>’ (2016)<em>: </em><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/554573/Putting_children_first_delivering_vision_excellent_childrens_social_care.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/554573/Putting_children_first_delivering_vision_excellent_childrens_social_care.pdf</a></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-06-30T13:25:58.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731571/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731571/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731571/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Children: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on the placement of responsibilities for family support and child protection services.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731572","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-06-30","<p>The site at Sandy lane was abandoned in October 2016 and from this point onwards there has been no site management. There have however been regular Police and Fire service patrols and the site is monitored using CCTV.</p><p> </p><p>The Environment Agency is working with Local Resilience Forum members, including Bassetlaw District Council, the Nottinghamshire Fire Service, Nottinghamshire County Council and Public Health England, to manage the risks at the site and is acting to clear the waste that also poses a risk to human health.</p><p> </p><p>There are three main waste streams which have been left at the site: mixed non-hazardous combustible waste in and around the transfer building; mixed construction and demolition (C&amp;D) non-combustible waste outside and the bags of polyurethane foam, mostly deposited in the centre of the site. The table below outlines the estimated costs associated with each waste stream. The cost of this clearance, excluding landfill tax have not been included as the landfill tax is not waived, which has been previously communicated by HMT to the HM for Bassetlaw.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Waste</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Estimated quantity (tonnes)</strong><strong><sup>1</sup></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Estimated Costs in £k (including Landfill Tax)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mixed C&amp;D non-combustible</p></td><td><p>20,000</p></td><td><p>3,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-Hazardous combustible</p></td><td><p>2,500</p></td><td><p>375</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Polyurethane foam</p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>20</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><sup>1</sup>The tonnages have been estimated by officers’ observations on site. A more accurate assessment of the volumes of waste present at the site would cost around £5K.</p><p> </p><p>The main environmental and health risk from the site is from the polyurethane foam left on site. The Environment Agency, county and district councils have set funds aside and are making plans to remove this foam as soon as possible.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Environment Agency has also been working in close partnership with Bassetlaw District Council, Notts Fire &amp; Rescue Service, Police, the County Council and Public Health England, to create a tactical plan which will be implemented in the event of a fire. The Notts Fire &amp; Rescue Service will shortly be entering the site and will attempt to move wastes around the site to allow for fire breaks and better access.</p><p> </p><p>The other environmental risks are in relation to the degradation of the waste. The Environment Agency, Fire and Rescue Service and Bassetlaw DC do have powers to intervene in exceptional circumstances where there is a serious risk to the environment and health.</p><p> </p><p>The Environment Agency is continuing its investigation into the former operators of the site. There is close contact about the site at official level across Government agencies. The Secretary of State has not discussed the site with Cabinet colleagues since his appointment on 11 June.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","600 ; 601 ; 602","2017-06-30T11:35:48.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731572/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731572/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731572/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-06-21","Waste Disposal: Worksop","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he has held discussions with the Secretary of State for Transport and the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government Secretary on the potential risk and costs of a fire at the abandoned waste site at Sandy Lane, Worksop.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731573","Department for Education","false","2017-06-27","<p>We want all pupils to benefit from a knowledge rich education. We will provide further details about the curriculum fund in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","658","2017-06-27T16:58:46.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731573/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731573/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731573/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Curriculum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on introducing a curriculum fund to encourage cultural and scientific institutions to help develop knowledge-rich materials for schools.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731574","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>Assessment in primary schools is a fundamental part of ensuring that every pupil acquires the sound grasp of the basics of literacy and numeracy that they need in order to succeed at secondary school and in later life. That is why pupils in Year 6 sit statutory tests in English reading, grammar, punctuation and spelling, and mathematics. We also collect teacher assessment data for English writing.</p><p>We have made clear our intention to establish a settled, proportionate primary assessment system for the long term, and we have recently conducted a public consultation on our proposals to achieve this. Further announcements will be made once we have considered the responses to that consultation.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-06-29T16:46:01.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731574/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731574/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731574/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Primary Education: Assessments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on assessments at the end of primary school.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731575","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>Parents value inspection reports as a reliable source of information about their children’s school. As part of Ofsted’s current school inspections, inspectors already consider the design and implementation of the school’s curriculum, and the extent to which the curriculum is broad and balanced.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is working with Ofsted to consider how parents can be given more information on what their children are taught.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-06-29T16:01:35.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731575/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731575/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731575/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Curriculum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on how Ofsted can give parents more information on what their children are being taught.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731576","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-06-30","<p>Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) came into existence on 1 June 2014 and ownership was transferred to new rehabilitation providers on 1 February 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The performance of CRCs, including compliance with Licence and Post-Sentence Supervision (PSS), is assessed through a range of service levels and through a robust contract management and assurance process. Performance information against these service levels is published quarterly, and the latest data can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/community-performance-quarterly-mi-update-to-december-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/community-performance-quarterly-mi-update-to-december-2016</a>. End state targets for some service levels were only expected to be met by February 2017, and this period is due for publication on 27 July 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Public protection is our top priority and we will take all necessary action to make sure the probation system is reducing reoffending and preventing future victims. We have undertaken an overarching review of probation, looking at the standards we set for providers and how we hold them to account and will be publishing our findings in due course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","380","2017-06-30T13:43:40.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731576/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731576/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731576/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-21","Probation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the proportion of offenders is who were recorded as having successfully completed their period of licence or post-sentence supervision in (a) England, (b) Wales and (c) each community rehabilitation company following a release from custody in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731577","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-06-30","<p>The Strategic Partner Gateway (SPG) has been available since September 2016, providing secure data exchange capability between nDelius and CRCs own offender case management systems once they are ready.</p><p> </p><p>There was a delay in implementing the SPG which was originally expected to be in place in the second quarter of 2015. This was due to extra work required on technical data exchange requirements, and design changes as a result of additional business processes that had been identified.</p><p> </p><p>The CRCs do not yet have their own case management systems in service. Following extensive testing and accreditation, the first anticipated cutover to a CRC’s own system and the SPG is currently planned to take place by early autumn 2017.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-06-30T13:46:11.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731577/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731577/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731577/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-21","Ministry of Justice: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, by what date his Department plans to deliver the strategic (IT) gateway; and what the reasons are for delay.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731578","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-06-30","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Community Rehabilitation Companies came into existence on 1 June 2014 and ownership was transferred to new rehabilitation providers on 1 February 2015. We have since undertaken an overarching review of probation, looking at the standards we set for providers and how we hold them to account and will be publishing our findings in due course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","376","2017-06-30T13:35:54.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731578/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731578/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731578/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-21","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many service users main contact with the community rehabilitation company is by telephone, in each community rehabilitation company in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731579","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>The Government is reviewing its approach ‎to the financing of teacher training and its relationship to wider student support. We will announce our conclusions in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","678 ; 679","2017-06-29T16:29:23.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731579/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731579/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731579/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on the repayment of student loans by teachers.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731580","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-06-30","<p>We recognise that the reforms to probation services led to a period of great change for staff. Staff in the National Probation Service (NPS) and Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs) were provided with support both during and after the transition to the new probation structures.</p><p> </p><p>CRCs are responsible for the welfare of the staff they employ. All suppliers were required to outline their employee incentive offer at the bidding stage, and these have been contractualised. We monitor CRCs closely through a robust contract management process.</p><p> </p><p>We have undertaken an overarching review of probation, looking at the standards we set for providers and how we hold them to account, and will be publishing our findings in due course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-06-30T13:41:06.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731580/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731580/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731580/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-21","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment the Government has made of staff moral in community rehabilitation companies in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","520"
