"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/724090","HM Treasury","false","2017-04-27","<p>The Soft Drinks Industry Levy comes into force in April 2018, and as such has raised no revenue in the last 12 months.</p><p> </p><p>At the Budget in March 2017, the Chancellor announced that the levy is now forecast to raise approximately £385m per annum from April 2018, which is less than the £520m originally forecast due to strong reformulation responses from the industry. This is a central forecast independently verified by the Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR).</p><p> </p><p>The Government will still fund the Department for Education’s budget with the £1 billion that the levy was originally expected to raise over this Parliament, including money to double the primary schools sports premium and deliver additional funding for school breakfast clubs, and £415 million to be invested in a new healthy pupils capital programme.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-04-27T07:57:45.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/724090/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/724090/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/724090/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-04-25","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much has been raised from the soft drinks industry levy in the last 12 months; and what estimate he has made of likely revenue from that levy in the next three years.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","71853"
